8. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 643566888
T1  - MONTEVIDEO'S OBESITY AND BARIATRIC SURGERY PROGRAM (PCOB): PREOPERATIVE ECHOCARDIOGRAMS ANALYSIS
T3  - 18th Conference in Internal Medicine. Lisbon Portugal.
A1  - Thomas E.
A1  - Bruno G.
A1  - Spangenberg L.
A1  - Vaucher A.
A1  - Huarte A. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background Obesity is a chronic epidemic disease that affects life quality and causes greater morbidity and mortality. It's an independent cardiovascular risk factor, developing symptomatic coronary disease, atrial fibrillation and heart failure (HF). Patients with advanced obesity stages who suffer from HF, excluding other aetiologies, are diagnosed of obesity cardiomyopathy characterized by a preserved left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF). Describe anatomical and functional left cardiac echocardiographic alterations in a population of morbid obese patients. Methods An analytical study was performed in Maciel's Hospital Obesity and Bariatric Surgery Program (Montevideo-Uruguay) between June 2014 and September 2016. The inclusion criteria were 18 to 64 years old, a body mass index (BMI) greater or equal to 40 kg/m2 or greater to 35 kg/m2 with comorbidities. Patients with cardiomyopathy of known aetiology, atrial fibrillation, hyperthyroidism and poor echocardiographic window were excluded. A preoperative transthoracic echocardiogram was performed. These variables were defined according the Interamerican Society of Echocardiography and Cardiovascular Imaging: left ventricle mass, left atrium diameter, left ventricle diastolic diameter, interventricular septum, posterior wall, LVEF and diastolic dysfunction (DD). The diagnosis of left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) was made based on the index of left ventricle mass indexed to high 2.7. These variables were analysed. Results We included 79 patients, 66 (83.5%) women, age average was 45.8 +/- 10.22 years. The median BMI was 53.1 +/- 9.05. Of these patients 50 (63.29%) had HT and 33 (41.77%) DM. LVH was diagnosed in 56 (70.88%), being the excentric hypertrophy pattern the most frequent (53.2%). 20.25% of the patients evidenced DD and 41.77% increased left atrial size. LVEF was greater than 50% in 97.5% of the cases. It was found a positive correlation (0.22) between BMI and LVH (p: 0.047). In order to understand which covariables are influencing LVH linear additive models were used. None of them were significative.Considering the Akaike's information criteria and the number of significant coefficients, the best model included IMC, LDL and HT variables (LVH~BMI + LDL + HT + BMI LDL). Contribution to the development LVH was 8.8 for HT and 1,55 for IMC. Conclusion Eccentric LVH is the most frequent echocardiographic alteration in obese patients. The most important variable related to LVH development is HT, but BMI is a significant factor implied.
