AN  - 626662627
ID  - 30835597 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=30835597]
T1  - Carnitine and chromium co-supplementation affects mental health, hormonal, inflammatory, genetic, and oxidative stress parameters in women with polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Jamilian M.
A1  - Foroozanfard F.
A1  - Kavossian E.
A1  - Aghadavod E.
A1  - Amirani E.
A1  - Mahdavinia M.
A1  - Mafi A.
A1  - Asemi Z. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Objective: The aim of this study was to evaluate the effect of the co-administration of carnitine and chromium on mental health, hormonal, inflammatory and genetic parameters in women with PCOS. Method(s): This randomized, double-blinded, placebo-controlled clinical trial was conducted on 54 subjects, aged 18-40 years old. Subjects were randomly allocated to take either 1000 mg/d carnitine plus 200 microg/d chromium as chromium picolinate (n = 26) or placebo (n = 27) for 12 weeks. Result(s): Carnitine and chromium co-supplementation, compared with the placebo, significantly improved beck depression inventory (beta - 0.84; 95% CI, -1.51, -0.17; p = 0.01), general health questionnaire scores (beta - 1.13; 95% CI, -2.13, -0.14; p = 0.02) and depression anxiety and stress scale scores (beta - 0.96; 95% CI, -0.78, -0.14; p = 0.02). Participants who received carnitine plus chromium supplements had significantly lower total testosterone (beta - 0.15 ng/mL; 95% CI, -0.24, -0.06; p = 0.002), hirsutism (beta - 0.48; 95% CI, -0.91, -0.06; p = 0.02), high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP) (beta - 1.02 mg/L; 95% CI, -1.79, -0.25; p = 0.01), and malondialdehyde (MDA) levels (beta - 0.38 micromol/L; 95% CI, -0.56, -0.20; p < 0.001), and higher total antioxidant capacity (TAC) levels (beta 107.18 mmol/L; 95% CI, 44.24, 170.12; p = 0.001) compared with the placebo. Moreover, carnitine and chromium co-supplementation upregulated gene expression of interleukin-6 (IL-6) (p = 0.02) and tumor necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) (p = 0.02) compared with the placebo. Conclusion(s): Overall, the co-administration of carnitine and chromium for 12 weeks to women with PCOS had beneficial effects on mental health parameters, serum total testosterone, mF-G scores, hs-CRP, TAC and MDA levels, and gene expression of IL-6 and TNF-alpha.Copyright © 2019, © 2019 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
