AN  - 2023301671
T1  - Evaluation of cases of puberty menorrhagia requiring in-patient care in a tertiary care Hospital in Jammu: A Retrospective study
A1  - Sharma H.
A1  - Dolma T.
A1  - Sharma D.
A1  - Angmo D.
A1  - Rab N.A.
A1  - Slathia N. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: Puberty menorrhagia, is defined asheavy bleeding that occurs between menarche and the age of 19 and lasts for more than seven days or more than 80 milliliters. Heavy menstrual bleeding is defined as excessive menstrual blood loss that interferes with a women's physical, social,emotional and material quality of life. There is, however, a dearth of study that is devoted exclusively to situations that require for in-patient care. Method(s): The present retrospective record based study was conducted in the Department Of Obstetrics And Gynaecology, SMGS Hospital Jammu with effect from July 2021 to July 2022. Data from all adolescent girls admitted for treatment of excessive vaginal bleeding who had a history of the condition and who were between the ages of menarche and 19 years, met all inclusion criteria, and did not meet any exclusion criteria, were included in the study. Result(s): The results of the present study demonstrated that individuals with puberty menorrhagia typically fall into the 10-14 age range, with anovulation and PCOS being the most common etiologies. Progesterone combined with blood, in addition to hematinics, tranexamic acid therapy, and COC combined with blood, are effective treatments for puberty menorrhagia. Conclusion(s): Menorrhagia during puberty may cause serious problems and necessitate blood transfusions. Although anovulation is the most frequent cause of Puberty menorrhagia, bleeding disorders, other medical conditions, and other organic factors must also be ruled out in any patient.Copyright © 2022, Anka Publishers. All rights reserved.
