68. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 640578500
T1  - Investigating the Genetic Signature of the Complications Associated with Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus in Emirati Patients: A Multicenter Study
T3  - 11th Emirates Diabetes and Endocrine Congress. Virtual.
A1  - Mussa B.M.
A1  - Abusnana S.
A1  - Hamoudi R.
A1  - Srivastava A.
A1  - Al-Habshi A.
A1  - Venkatachalam T.
A1  - Abdelgadir E.
A1  - Bashier A.
A1  - Al Awadi F.
A1  - Hafidh K. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: Diabetes mellitus (DM) is one of the most challenging health problems in the Gulf countries including the United Arab Emirates. IDF recent reports have shown that over one million children and adolescents have Type 1 diabetes (T1DM) which is a chronic autoimmune disease characterized by insulin deficiency and hyperglycemia. Although several investigations have been conducted to understand the nature of T1DM, there are still gaps in our understanding of the complications that are associated with this disease. These complications influence the quality of life of this group of patients and shape their involvement in establishing a better future. Accordingly, the present study was designed to investigate the genetic signature of the complications that are associated with T1DM in Emirati patients. Method(s): The present study included a total of 58 Emirati participants aged above 18 years and with a BMI 25 kg/m2. Forty-five of these participants had a confirmed diagnosis of Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus (T1DM) and recruited from three hospitals: University Hospital Sharjah, Dubai Hospital and Rashid Hospital. Healthy Emirati participants with matching baseline characteristics were recruited as control participants. Blood samples were collected from the participants and following laboratory tests were conducted: haemoglobin A1c, fasting blood glucose, insulin levels, total cholesterol, triglycerides, high-density lipoprotein, low-density lipoprotein, c-reactive protein, Creatinine and C-peptide. Furthermore, for genetic and transcriptomic analysis, RNA was extracted from these blood samples and this was followed by comprehensive bioinformatics analysis. Results and Discussion: Using a whole transcriptome sequencing, differentially expressed genes (upregulated genes and downregulated genes) were identified for the following six groups: TIDM without complications, TIDM with hyperlipidemia, TIDM with neuropathy, T1DM with PCOS, T1DM with ketoacidosis, and T1DM with hypothyroidism. In addition, top functional pathways were identified for all the complications that are associated with T1DM in this group of patients. Interestingly, significant number of differentially expressed genes were shared between some of these complications and this includes 54, 72, 28 genes shared between the T1DM without complications and the groups with hyperlipidemia, neuropathy and PCOS, respectively. These findings will facilitate a predication about T1DM patients who are more susceptible to develop complications. This further will support the processes of screening and early interventions. Conclusion(s): This present multi-center study has identified new genetic signatures of the complications that are associated with T1DM and provide novel details about the differentially expressed genes that can be used to screen for the possibility of developing several complications in T1DM.
