200. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639863264
T1  - Factors influencing participation rates in a digital health survey. A nationwide study among Norwegian prostate cancer patients and a matched control group
T3  - 29th Annual Conference of the International Society for Quality of Life Research, ISOQOL 2022. Prague Czechia.
A1  - Gjelsvik Y.M.
A1  - Myklebust T.A.
A1  - Johannesen T.B. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Aims: Since 2020, the Cancer Registry of Norway (CRN) has invited newly diagnosed prostate cancer (PCa) patients and a control group consisting of men with no history of PCa to a digital health survey. The invitations are sent using the official health portal Helsenorge.no, or an official digital mailbox. 16% of PCa patients and 26% of the controls did not use Helsenorge.no or an official digital mailbox in 2021. Thus, the CRN was unable to invite these persons to the health survey. The survey being solely digital might lead to selection bias. We wanted to identify factors related to the likelihood of digital participation both for PCa patients and a control group with no history of PCa. Method(s): All Norwegian men diagnosed in 2017-2019 and a control group with no history of PCa were invited to a 3-year survey on men's health, Prostate Cancer Outcomes Norway (PCO-Norway). The men who could not be invited digitally, received an invitation which included a paper questionnaire and a pre-paid return envelope in the mail. Participants diagnosed with PCa in 2017 and 2018 and controls participating in the baseline round of the survey were grouped according to response method. Associations with age at diagnosis, living situation, education level and global health status/ quality of life (QoL) from the EORTC QLQ-C30 were analysed using multivariable Poisson regressions with digital participation as the outcome. Result(s): Among 5 229 participants diagnosed with PCa in 2017 and 2018, men who submitted a paper questionnaire were more likely to be older (RR = 0.98, 95% CI 0.97-0.98), live alone (RR = 0.87, 95% CI 0.77-1.00), have a lower education level (highest vs. lowest education level, RR = 2.28, 95% CI 1.97-2.65) and a lower EORTC global health status/QoL score (RR = 1.04, 95% CI 1.01-1.08) than the PCa patients participating digitally. The same pattern emerged in the control group. Conclusion(s): The results suggest that a solely digital survey may lead to selection bias. More detailed analyses on disease factors and other self-reported outcomes among the two groups of participants in PCO-Norway are being planned.
