201. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639862865
T1  - One report, multiple aims: Orthopaedic surgeons vary in how they use patient-reported outcomes with patients
T3  - 29th Annual Conference of the International Society for Quality of Life Research, ISOQOL 2022. Prague Czechia.
A1  - Lavallee D.
A1  - Rothrock N.
A1  - Chen A.
A1  - Franklin P. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Aims: Knee and hip osteoarthritis (OA) are conditions that cause progressive pain and functional loss leading patients to seek operative and non-operative healthcare to relieve symptoms and improve quality of life. In orthopaedics, PRO measures (PROMs) are considered standard of care today for assessing OA severity and treatment outcomes as well as being utilized in care quality metrics by payers and policy makers. However, no clear guidelines exist for integrating PROM data to guide treatment decisions. To address this gap, the Arthritis care through Shared Knowledge (ASK) study, a PCORI-funded initiative, deploys a PROM-based shared decision report to guide OA patients and their surgeons in discussions around surgical and non-surgical treatment decisions. We conducted structured qualitative interviews with participating surgeons to assess their goals and uses of the PROM-based report. Method(s): Surgeons involved in the ASK study for at least 6 months and actively enrolling patients into the study were invited to participate in a semi-structured interview lasting 30 min. Open-ended questions explored how the surgeon used report content, features that were helpful, confusing, or could be improved, and how use of the report fit into the surgeon's workflow. We used a directed content analysis approach. Result(s): Of the 16 eligible surgeons, 11 agreed to participate with 9 completing the interview and 2 withdrawing due to work demands. We identified 8 themes related to PROM-based report use: Acceptability, Patient Characteristics, Communication Goals, Useful Content, Not Useful Content, Challenges, Training Needs, and Recommended Improvements. Additional sub-themes emerged for Communication Goals (7) and Challenges (8; see Table 1). All surgeons shared positive feedback about using the report as part of clinical care. While surgeons described the use of the report to achieve different goals, the most common use (89%) related to setting expectations for postsurgical outcomes. Conclusion(s): Surgeons tailor their use of a standardized PROM-based report with individual patients to achieve a range of aims. This study suggests multiple opportunities to further our understanding of the ways PROMs can be used in clinical practice. The way PROM information is displayed visually and multicomponent reports are assembled can facilitate diverse aims. (Table Presented).
