202. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639822628
T1  - Is Progesterone Replacement Therapy Effective in Managing Heavy and Irregular Menstrual Bleeding and Associated Severe Dysmenorrhoea in the First Few Years after Onset of Menstruation in Young Girls due to Physiological Progesterone Deficiency Associated with Nonovulatory Menstrual Cycles in a Still-Maturing Hypothalamic-Pituitary- Ovarian axis?
T3  - Annual Scientific Meeting of the Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, RANZCOG 2022. Gold Coast, QLD Australia.
A1  - Venables A.
A1  - O'brien B.
A1  - Viswanathan D.
A1  - Kimble R. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introduction: In the first-to- five years of postmenarche, ovulatory cycles range from 7.1 to 56% (Apter 1980) due to an immature Hypothalamic-Pituitary- Ovarian (HPO)axis, causing a physiological progesterone deficiency. This impact of unopposed oestrogen on the endometrium is manifest by heavy menstrual bleeding (HMB), irregular cycles and associated pain from both vaginal egress and retrograde menstruation. Progesterone replacement therapy should be considered first-line for patients in this cohort. Aim(s): Evaluation of the effectiveness of cyclical progesterone replacement therapy for patients with symptomatic likely non-ovulatory cycles in the early postmenarche age group. Method(s): Queensland Children's Hospital Paediatric and Adolescent Gynaecology data between 2016 and 2020 were retrospectively analysed. Heavy menstrual bleeding, dysmenorrhoea, cycle irregularity and self-reported improvement in quality of life were compared before and after treatment with progesterone. Result(s): One hundred and seventeen patients were included. Oral progesterone therapy reduced HMB, cycle irregularity and dysmenorrhoea in 80%, 65% and 79% of patients, respectively. 93%, 83% and 91% of patients given oral or depot progesterone had reduced HMB, cycle irregularity and dysmenorrhoea, respectively. Overall, 88 % of patients reported improvement in quality of life. Discussion(s): Progesterone replacement therapy is the appropriate first-line treatment for this early postmenarche age group to treat menstrual disorders due to anovulatory cycles. A thorough explanation of this physiological phenomenon to patients and carers assists with reassurance and compliance with treatment and allays anxiety about the not uncommon OCP prescription for this cohort.
