204. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639758426
T1  - Time-Restricted Eating for the Treatment of Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: A Pilot Study
T3  - 40th Annual Meeting of the Obesity Society at Obesityweek. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Cienfuegos S.
A1  - Ezpeleta M.
A1  - Lin S.
A1  - Gonzalez F.
A1  - Varady K. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: Time restricted eating (TRE) involves limiting the eating window to a specific number of hours per day (4-10 h) and water fasting for the remaining hours. No studies to date have examined TRE for the treatment of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). We performed a pilot study to compare the effects of TRE versus daily calorie restriction (CR) on body weight, androgen markers, glycemic control, mood, and quality of life (QOL) in woman with suspected PCOS. Method(s): 15 reproductive age women with obesity and suspected PCOS based on having a high free androgen index (FAI: 100 x serum testosterone [T] / sex hormone binding globulin [SHBG]) >3 nmol/l, an established predictor for PCOS. Subjects were randomized to 1 of 3 interventions for 12 weeks: 1) TRE (n = 5; 8-h eating, 16-h fasting), 2) CR (n = 5; 25% energy restriction daily), or 3) control (n = 5; usual diet). Result(s): By week 12, body weight decreased significantly (p = 0.02) more in the TRE group (-2.3 +/- 0.3%; -2.5 +/- 0.3 kg) versus CR (-0.3 +/- 0.9%; -0.3 +/- 0.9 kg) and controls. Fat mass also decreased (p = 0.01) more in the TRE group (-1.6 +/- 0.6 kg) versus CR (-0.2 +/- 0.9 kg) and controls. Visceral fat mass and waist circumference were also reduced more (p = 0.03) in the TRE group versus CR and controls. Total testosterone and sex hormone binding globulin (SHBG) remained unchanged. However, there was a trend (p = 0.10) towards greater reductions in FAI by TRE (-21 +/- 9%) versus CR (-5 +/- 7%) and controls. In addition, depression score decreased significantly (p = 0.005) in the TRE group (-57 +/- 3%) compared to CR (+21 +/- 27%) and controls. Lean mass, fasting glucose, fasting insulin, insulin sensitivity and QOL did not differ between the groups by week 12. Conclusion(s): These findings suggest that TRE causes greater reductions in body weight, fat mass, visceral fat, and depression score, versus CR, in women with obesity and suspected PCOS. Further investigation is warranted to confirm whether TRE can improve hyperandrogenism.
