208. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 639459051
T1  - Pediatric hidradenitis suppurativa: Characterizing the disease
T3  - 47th Annual Meeting of the Society for Pediatric Dermatology. Indianapolis, IN United States.
A1  - Andrews L.
A1  - Shope C.
A1  - Robinson-Pirotte I.
A1  - Cotton C. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: Pediatric hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) is chronic inflammatory skin condition involving the hair follicles, most commonly involving the skin folds and genitalia. HS is attributed to androgen excess and hormonal imbalances along with an established genetic component. A diagnosis of HS has been shown to have an especially profound impact on patients' quality of life. There is a lack of research describing HS in the pediatric population, therefore, with this study we aimed to accurately characterize the pediatric HS patient population. Methodology: We distributed REDCap surveys to pediatric HS patients and/or guardians who are members of the patient advocacy organization, HS Connect. Participants were eligible to participate if they developed HS symptoms before the age of 18 years old and if they received an HS diagnosis at the age of 25 years or younger. A one-sample t-test was performed using SPSS to analyze data. Result(s): There were 99 survey respondents, the majority of whom were Caucasian females. Patients were most often between the ages of 26 to 35 or 36 to 45 at the time of the survey (31.2% each) with a Hurley Stage of 2 (45.8%, p-value <0.001), and were between the ages of 10 and 14 when their symptoms of HS first appeared (64.7%, p-value <0.001). The most common area affected was the groin (88.5%, p-value <0.001). Only 39.6% had a family history of HS (p-value <0.001). Patients were often overweight or obese (66.7%, p-value <0.001), with co-morbid mood disorders (61.5%, p-value <0.001), acne (26%, p-value <0.001), and PCOS (26%, p-value <0.001). It took most patients 10 years to receive a diagnosis of HS (47.9%, p-value <0.001), and this diagnosis was most commonly made by a dermatologist (47.9%, p-value <0.001). Conclusion(s): Patients diagnosed with pediatric HS first experienced symptoms during early adolescence. However, a substantial time lag existed between symptom onset and HS diagnosis. These patients suffer from moderate severity of disease accompanied by a variety of physical and psychiatric comorbidities, which may interfere with daily activities, cause pain, and lead to social embarrassment. With a better understanding of pediatric HS, future research can be performed to establish guidelines aimed at ameliorating the deleterious effects of this disease.
