211. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2020471100
T1  - OBSTACLES IN THE AIRWAY: SUBACUTE DYSPNEA AND MANAGEMENT OF CENTRAL AIRWAY OBSTRUCTION
T3  - CHEST 2022 Annual Meeting. Nashville United States.
A1  - MURPHY M.
A1  - KODELA J.
A1  - N SOOD R. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - SESSION TITLE: Other Malignancies with Pulmonary Features Case Posters SESSION TYPE: Case Report Posters PRESENTED ON: 10/17/2022 12:15 pm - 01:15 pm INTRODUCTION: Central airway obstruction (CAO) occurs in 20-30% of lung cancer. Tracheal adenoid cystic carcinoma, a rare tumor, comprises ~0.2% of lung cancers. Here we present a case of CAO secondary to tracheal adenoid cystic carcinoma, highlighting the role of bronchoscopy in palliation of symptoms, bridge to definitive therapy, and longer quality-adjusted survival. CASE PRESENTATION: A 60-year-old woman with 40-pack-year smoking history presented with acute worsening of progressive exertional dyspnea. She reported associated orthopnea and cough productive of brown-flecked sputum but denied weight loss, fevers, or night sweats. She received no recent medical care and took no medications. Vitals were notable for tachypnea and oximetry of 98% on room air. On physical exam, she had accessory muscle retractions, inspiratory stridor, and expiratory wheezing. Initial labs notable for hemoglobin 16.4 (15.5) mg/dL, hematocrit 47.5% (45), and arterial pH 7.3 (7.4) and pCO2 62 (40) mmHg. She was treated with nebulized albuterol, ipratropium, racemic epinephrine and intravenous steroids with improved hypercapnia. X-rays of the chest and neck were unremarkable; subsequent CT of the chest and neck revealed circumferential soft tissue thickening of the mid-to-distal trachea ranging from the thoracic inlet to the aortic arch, with severe luminal narrowing. She was admitted to the ICU, managed on heliox, and underwent rigid/flexible bronchoscopy with debridement, biopsy, balloon dilation, and hybrid metallic stent deployment. Pathology results favored a diagnosis of primary tracheal adenoid cystic carcinoma. FDG-PET CT was negative for distant metastasis. DISCUSSION: Adenoid cystic carcinoma is rare tumor for which definitive management is endoscopic or open resection and adjuvant chemoradiation, although recurrence is frequent with 40-45% 5-year survival. Due to the size of the tumor, our patient was not a surgical candidate and was started on chemoradiation. Her course was complicated by two subsequent acute presentations of hypoxic respiratory failure, two and three months from her initial encounter. Each required bronchoscopy for dilation and obstructive granulation tissue debridement, the first requiring removal of the dislodged initial stent, and the second with silicon stent replacement. Bronchoscopy does not increase survival but poses no risk of stent-related mortality and offers an emergent therapeutic bridge to definitive therapy that may increase survival. Bronchoscopy palliates symptoms with improved Borg Scale scores and longer quality-adjusted survival, but may require revision. Following her last revision our patient was resumed on radiotherapy. CONCLUSION(S): -Bronchoscopy is used for biopsy diagnosis -Brochoscopy itself does not increase survival but is a therapeutic bridge to definitive therapy -Bronchoscopy palliates symptoms for longer quality-adjusted survival -Revision bronchoscopy is common Reference #1: Ost DE, Ernst A, Grosu HB, Lei X, Diaz-Mendoza J, Slade M, Gildea TR, Machuzak MS, Jimenez CA, Toth J, Kovitz KL, Ray C, Greenhill S, Casal RF, Almeida FA, Wahidi MM, Eapen GA, Feller-Kopman D, Morice RC, Benzaquen S, Tremblay A, Simoff M; AQuIRE Bronchoscopy Registry. Therapeutic bronchoscopy for malignant central airway obstruction: success rates and impact on dyspnea and quality of life. Chest. 2015 May;147(5):1282-1298. Reference #2: Wood DE, Liu YH, Vallieres E, Karmy-Jones R, Mulligan MS. Airway stenting for malignant and benign tracheobronchial stenosis. Ann Thorac Surg. 2003 Jul;76(1):167-72; discussion 173-4. Reference #3: Ong P, Grosu HB, Debiane L, et al. Long-term quality-adjusted survival following therapeutic bronchoscopy for malignant central airway obstruction. Thorax 2019;74:141-156. DISCLOSURES: No relevant relationships by Jennifer Kodela No relevant relationships by Michael Murphy No relevant relationships by Rahul SoodCopyright © 2022 American College of Chest Physicians
