212. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2020470834
T1  - EFFICACY OF TEZEPELUMAB IN PATIENTS WITH SEVERE, UNCONTROLLED ASTHMA BY SMOKING HISTORY: POST HOC ANALYSIS OF THE PHASE 3 NAVIGATOR STUDY
T3  - CHEST 2022 Annual Meeting. Nashville United States.
A1  - CASTRO M.
A1  - COOK W.
A1  - AMBROSE C.
A1  - W LINDSLEY A.
A1  - HUNTER G.
A1  - MARTIN N.E.I.L.
A1  - PONNARAMBIL S. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - SESSION TITLE: Tobacco Use, Risk Factors, and Managing Patients with Pulmonary Diseases SESSION TYPE: Rapid Fire Original Inv PRESENTED ON: 10/19/2022 11:15 am - 12:15 pm PURPOSE: Smoking is associated with more severe asthma symptoms and reduced treatment response. Although smoking cessation can improve symptoms, little is known about the efficacy of biologic treatment in former smokers. Tezepelumab, a human monoclonal antibody, blocks thymic stromal lymphopoietin (TSLP), an epithelial cytokine involved in asthma pathogenesis. In the phase 3 NAVIGATOR study (NCT03347279), tezepelumab significantly reduced exacerbations and improved lung function, asthma control and health-related quality of life versus placebo in patients with severe, uncontrolled asthma. This post hoc analysis assessed the efficacy of tezepelumab in NAVIGATOR patients who were former smokers and who had never smoked. METHOD(S): NAVIGATOR was a multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled study. Patients (12-80 years old), who were not current smokers and were receiving medium- or high-dose inhaled corticosteroids and >= 1 additional controller medication with or without oral corticosteroids (OCS), were randomized 1:1 to receive tezepelumab 210 mg or placebo subcutaneously every 4 weeks for 52 weeks. Former smokers with a smoking history of < 10 pack years who stopped smoking, vaping or using e-cigarettes >= 6 months before their first visit were eligible for enrolment. The annualized asthma exacerbation rate (AAER) over 52 weeks and change from baseline to week 52 in pre-bronchodilator (BD) forced expiratory volume in 1 second (FEV1) were assessed in former smokers and never smokers. RESULT(S): Of 1059 patients included, 20% were former smokers (tezepelumab, n = 99; placebo, n = 110), with a smoking history of 4.3 and 5.2 mean pack years, respectively. At baseline, a higher proportion of former smokers than never smokers were male, had experienced > 2 exacerbations, had lower baseline fractional exhaled nitric oxide level and were receiving maintenance OCS. Among placebo recipients, the AAER over 52 weeks was higher in former smokers (2.58 [95% confidence interval (CI): 1.97-3.39]) than never smokers (1.98 [95% CI: 1.71-2.28]). Tezepelumab reduced the AAER over 52 weeks versus placebo by 48% (95% CI: 21-65) and 58% (95% CI: 48-66) in former smokers and never smokers, respectively. Improvement from baseline to week 52 in pre-BD FEV1 was greater with tezepelumab than with placebo in former smokers (least-squares mean, 0.24 L vs 0.08 L; difference, 0.17 L [95% CI: 0.05-0.28]) and never smokers (least-squares mean, 0.23 L vs 0.10 L; difference, 0.13 L [95% CI: 0.07-0.18]). CONCLUSION(S): Tezepelumab reduced exacerbations and improved lung function versus placebo in former smokers and never smokers with severe, uncontrolled asthma. CLINICAL IMPLICATIONS: This analysis demonstrates the efficacy of tezepelumab in a broad population of patients with severe, uncontrolled asthma, including patients who were former smokers and who had never smoked. DISCLOSURES: Employee relationship with AstraZeneca Please note: >$100000 by Christopher Ambrose, value=Salary Principal Investigator relationship with PCORI Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding Principal Investigator relationship with AstraZeneca Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with AstraZeneca Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Principal Investigator relationship with Novartis Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding Consultant relationship with Novartis Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Consulting fee Principal Investigator relationship with GSK Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with GSK Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Principal Investigator relationship with Sanofi-Aventis Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with Sanofi-Aventis Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Consultant relationship with Sanofi-Aventis Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Consulting fee Consultant relationship with Ongoing Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Consulting fee Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with Teva Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with Genentech Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Consultant relationship with Genentech Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Consulting fee Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with Regeneron Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Author relationship with Elsevier Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Royalty Principal Investigator relationship with Shionogi Please note: Ongoing by Mario Castro, value=Study Funding University Study Grant relationship with Pulmatrix Please note: ongoing Added 03/30/2022 by Mario Castro, value=Grant/Research Support Consultant relationship with Merck Please note: ongoing Added 03/30/2022 by Mario Castro, value=Consulting fee Speaker/Speaker's Bureau relationship with Amgen Please note: ongoing Added 03/30/2022 by Mario Castro, value=Honoraria Employee relationship with AstraZeneca Please note: current since 2005 by William Cook, value=Salary Employee Employee relationship with Amgen, Inc. Please note: 8/2020 to present Added 03/29/2022 by Andrew Lindsley, value=Salary and stock Share holder relationship with GSK Please note: >$100000 by Neil Martin, value=Salary Employee relationship with Astrazeneca Please note: 2012 to present by Sandhia Ponnarambil, value=SalaryCopyright © 2022 American College of Chest Physicians
