218. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638513437
T1  - PCOS symptom recognition and diagnosis: Time for better education and clinical resources
T3  - Royal College of Obstretriscians and Gynaecologists World Congress, RCOG 2022. London United Kingdom.
A1  - Ali Z.
A1  - Vasavan T.
A1  - Ghani M.
A1  - Waskett E.
A1  - Getreu N.
A1  - O'Neill H. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Objective: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is an endocrine condition estimated to affect approximately 20% of women worldwide (Escobar-Morreale, 2018). Despite its prevalence and debilitating symptoms which impact quality of life, the journey to diagnosis can be challenging (Gibson-Helm et al.,2017). The study aims to understand methods that could reduce diagnosis timelines and improve management strategies for PCOS patients. Design(s): A cross-sectional study was used to investigate the current barriers to diagnosis and management of PCOS in women of reproductive age. Method(s): Participants aged 18 or older with an existing or suspected PCOS diagnosis were invited to complete an online survey across a period of 16 days in January and February 2022. The survey was presented on Typeform and disseminated via the social media platforms Instagram, Twitter and LinkedIn. The study was approved by the Hertility Health Research Ethics Committee. Of the 292 responses, 165 responses of those with a formal PCOS diagnosis were included in the analysis. Descriptive statistics are presented. Result(s): Of the 165 responses included, anxiety (74.5%), irregular menstrual cycles (67.3%) and weight-related concerns (64.8%) were most commonly reported. In the United Kingdom (UK), diagnosis of PCOS in the majority of cases (65.5%) was made by a General Practitioner (GP) as opposed to outside the UK, where the majority (82.5%) were diagnosed by a specialist such as a gynaecologist or fertility specialist. Upon receiving their diagnosis, 65.5% understood what PCOS was, but 54.5% were not satisfied with the advice provided to manage their condition. Despite mental health-related symptoms being the most frequently reported (77%), only 7.9% reported mental health management strategies being a topic of focus during consultation(s). The majority (88.4%) of participants looked for extra information after their consultation(s), however, only 48% used official websites such as the National Health Service (NHS), whilst most participants (53.4%) relied on social media. When asked which support pathways participants thought would improve symptom management, referral to a specialist clinician (87.8%), mental health support (53.3%), expert nutrition (38.2%) and exercise advice (22.4%), and educational resources (34%) were most frequently selected. Conclusion(s): Unsatisfactory management by healthcare providers and limited access to speciality support for management of PCOS-associated symptoms lead to a heavy reliance on unregulated channels to obtain reproductive health information, highlighting the need for better educational resources and accessible symptom management pathways.
