219. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638513006
T1  - Prevalence of female infertility in the UK armed forces
T3  - Royal College of Obstretriscians and Gynaecologists World Congress, RCOG 2022. London United Kingdom.
A1  - Thiel M.
A1  - Wild S.
A1  - Anderson R.
A1  - Bhattacharya S.
A1  - Greeves J. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Objective: The aims of this study were to determine the prevalence of self-reported infertility among UK servicewomen, compare the prevalence to non-military groups; and identify which factors were associated with infertility in this population. Design(s): This was a cross-sectional study of UK servicewomen and comparison populations. Female Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) officers and non-military non-MPS sisters of participants served as occupational and civilian controls Methods: An electronic questionnaire was developed, piloted and distributed to all eligible UK servicewomen (n = 14,650) and MPS officers (8,262) between November 2018 and August 2019. Non-military non-MPS sisters of participants were recruited using a snowball technique. We estimated a sample of 4898 servicewomen would give a precision of 1% around infertility prevalence estimates. Data collected included pregnancy history, time to each pregnancy and self-reported potential risk factors for infertility. Prevalence of infertility was defined as the proportion of women at risk of pregnancy who had not become pregnant within 12 months. Only women with pregnancy outcomes, or with fully tested fertility (12 months or more of exposure) were included in the denominator. Multi-variable regression was used to adjust for confounding factors. Ethics approval was granted by the Ministry of Defence Research Ethics Committee. Result(s): Participants included 4836 servicewomen, 1237 MPS officers and 435 sisters (estimated response rates 33%, 15% and 8%). Prevalence of self-reported infertility was 31.7% (95% CI: 29.9-33.5) in servicewomen, 36.3% (33.1-39.7) in MPS and 24.4% (19.6-29.8) in sisters. Age, polycystic ovary syndrome, endometriosis, fibroids, tubal and pelvic surgery, hysterectomy and short General Health Questionnaire score of 4 or more were identified as confounding factors. The adjusted odds ratio (aOR) for infertility was 1.0 (95% CI: 0.8-1.2) for servicewomen compared to MPS officers, and 1.5 (95% CI: 1.1-2.0) for servicewomen compared to sisters. Conclusion(s): Almost one in three servicewomen at risk of pregnancy report infertility. This is a significantly higher proportion than in sisters and reported UK population data (up to one in five). Study limitations include a lower response rate in the control groups with associated potential for response bias and potential over-estimation of infertility if fertile women are more likely to leave the military or MPS. Despite these limitations, this is a large study which is likely to report the most accurate prevalence estimate of self-reported infertility in UK servicewomen. Future cohort studies would help extend understanding of the influence of occupation on infertility.
