T3  - Neuromodulation: The Science and New York City Neuromodulation 2019 Conference. Napa United States.
A1  - Chokshi K.
A1  - Yih C.
A1  - Sackheim K. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Case Description: This is the case of a 35 year old female presenting to pain medicine clinic with three years of aching pelvic pain, vaginismus and spasms of her pelvic floor. The patient reported multiple laparoscopies for endometriosis after which the pain had worsened. She had a history of hypothyroidism, Hashimoto's thyroidits, interstitial cystitis, polycystic ovarian syndrome, fibromyalgia, factor V bleeding deficiency, post-traumatic stress disorder and depression. She had tried physical therapy, pelvic floor therapy, acupuncture, TENs, yoga, massage and other modalities over the years to which the pain did not improve. Medications trialed included Morphine sulfate extended release tablets, Vicodin, Percocet, Tramadol, Cymbalta and Fentanyl patches which helped the pain minimally. A diagnosis of chronic pelvic pain and vaginismus was made and the patient returned to pain clinic for a trial of Botulinum toxin injections for the pelvic floor. 10 units of Botox were injected to each obturator internus lateral to the cervix, 20 units into the iliococcygeus bilaterally and 20 units into the pubococcygeus bilaterally. The patient tolerated the procedure well and returned to clinic after 3 months with 80-90% pain relief. The patient reported significant improvement in quality of life after the procedure Discussion: Chronic pelvic pain affects approximately 26% of the world's female population. It is often described as non-cyclic, persistent pain in the pelvic region that lasts more than six months. While there may be no specific etiology, it is essential that clinicians account for cognitive, behavioral, sexual, emotional and functional factors contributing to the severity of the disease. Botulinim toxin injections serve as a promising potential therapeutic intervention to help treat muscle spasms commonly associated with chronic pelvic pain. Their safety, efficacy and favorable side effect profile make it a promising choice to relive the prolonged burden of disease. Conclusion(s): Chronic pelvic pain is challenging and complex condition that can have a tremendous impact on a patient's physical, emotional and functional state severely impacting their quality of life. Diagnosis and treatment can often be delayed due to non-specific symptoms. Care must be provided through a multidisciplinary approach that accounts for the biopsychosocial factors contributing to the burden of disease. Further research is needed to understand clinically effective dosage of Botox, sites, number of injections and treatment timeline to alleviate global morbidity and disability. Disclosure: Krupali Chokshi, MD: None, Christopher Yih, DO: None, Kimberly Sackheim, MD: NoneCopyright © 2022
