223. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638403207
T1  - A Case of Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis and Obstructive Sleep Apnea Treated with High Flow Nasal Cannula
T3  - International Conferenceof the American Thoracic Society, ATS 2022. San Francisco, CA United States.
A1  - Zuccarini G.
A1  - Esposito A.
A1  - Prosperi P.
A1  - Spacone A. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introduction Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) is a chronic and progressive lung disease with high mortality rates.Patients with IPF, often develops progressive daytime hypoxia or desaturation during sleep, with or without apnea, which complicates the clinical presentation. Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) and other sleep breathing disorders worsen the quality of sleep and increase the mortality rate, especially in patients with others respiratory conditions. Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) is the gold standard treatment for OSA.High flow nasal cannula (HFNC) oxygen therapy is used in adults in different clinical settings: hypoxemic respiratory failure, exacerbation of COPD, ARDS, postextubation, sleep apnea, acute heart failure and conditions entailing do-not-intubate orders. In many studies HFNC decreases breathing frequency and work of breathing and reduces the need for respiratory support escalation.We describe a case of IPF and OSA treated with HFNC. Description We observed a man (74 years old, ex-smoker, body mass index: 24 Kg /m2) with IPF since 2 years, in treatment with antifibrotic drugs. He reported dyspnea, excessive daytime sleepiness (Epworth Sleepiness Score (ESS) of 14/24, weakness, snoring, disturbed sleep and headaches. Blood gas analysis at rest revealed mild hypoxemia (pO2 64 mmHg, pCO2 35 mmHg, pH 7.36, SatO2 95%) and a home sleep apnea test (HSAT) overnight in room air showed a moderate OSA (Apnea/Hypopnea index - AHI - 15.9/h, with a mean duration of 17 sec, average SpO2 was 91.7, time spent in SpO2 under 90% (T<90) was 30%, and snoring time in percentage was 40% (Fig.1).HFNC treatment was started (myAIRVO TM using OptiflowTM + cannula, Fisher & Paykel Healthcare, temperature 34degreeC, flow rate 40 L/min, FiO2 28%) during the night for eight hours and HSAT was repeated with this therapy which had a benefit and corrected his polygraphic indexes (fig.1).At the 3 months follow-up the patient's quality of life had improved and his ESS improved form 14/24 to 9/24. Discussion and Conclusion We observed the positive outcomes of HFNC therapy in a patient with IPF and OSA. This suggests a role in the alleviation of upper airway obstruction by the modest increases of nasopharyngeal pressure delivered using the HFNC system.In IPF, HFNC appears to be an alternative modality for treating hypoxemia in patients who do notrequire immediate intubation, by providing better oxygenation, dyspnea relief and comfort. For this case HFNC has been used to success treat OSA when combined with early secondary acute respiratory failure due to IPF. (Figure Presented).
