226. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 637739582
T1  - Evaluation of Mineral Profile in Patients of Polycystic Ovary Syndrome
T3  - 2nd International e-Conference, BMS e-CON-2021. Virtual.
A1  - Khushbu S.
A1  - Rubal S.
A1  - Pragati U.
A1  - Bushra F.
A1  - Maheep S. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introduction: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a complex condition characterized by elevated levels of androgens, menstrual irregularities, or small cysts on one or both ovaries. Identification of the actual biochemical derangement may be helpful in treatment of the particular disorder and over all in improving the quality of life. Aim(s): The present study was planned to assess mineral profile (serum calcium, phosphorus, magnesium) in PCOS patients as compared to healthy subjects. Material(s) and Method(s): A total of 54 females suffering from PCOS, age between 18-45 years, and 50 age matched healthy control were enrolled for the study. Women who are on drugs or hormone therapy were excluded from the study. Above mineral profile was evaluated and results were represented as mean+/-SD. Result(s): Mean level of serum calcium among PCOS females was 8.23+/-1.55 and among control group was 9.28+/-0.63. Mean value of serum phosphorus among PCOS females was 5.43+/-1.64 and among control group 4.03+/-0.60. Mean levels of serum magnesium in PCOS females was 2.33+/-0.82and in control group 1.75+/-0.35. All the three above minerals were statistically significant (p<0.0001). Serum calcium levels were found to be decreased among PCOS females as compared to the control group while serum phosphorus and serum magnesium levels were raised among PCOS females comparatively to the control group. Conclusion(s): The study indicates a relation between above minerals profile in PCOS females. Imbalance of these minerals may lead to other manifestations like muscle pain, nausea, and other long term implications. Evaluation of these minerals may help in providing optimal treatment and relieving the misery of female suffering from PCOS.
