370. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2011622727
T1  - HST5040: An investigational oral small molecule therapy entering phase 2 clinical development for methylmalonic (MMA) and propionic (PA) acidemias
T3  - 2021 ACMG Annual Clinical Genetics Meeting. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Cox G.
A1  - Armstrong A.
A1  - Waller M.
A1  - Hayes M.
A1  - Collado M.S.
A1  - Henke B.
A1  - Summar M.
A1  - Wamhoff B.
A1  - Reardon J.
A1  - Figler R.
A1  - Johns B.
A1  - Chapman K. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Methylmalonic (MMA) and propionic (PA) acidemias are organic acidemias caused by deficient activity of the mitochondrial enzymes methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (MUT) and propionyl-CoA carboxylase (PCC), respectively. These enzymes catalyze sequential steps in the propionate pathway, which is the final common pathway for the catabolism of certain amino acids (valine, isoleucine, methionine, and threonine), odd-chain fatty acids, and propionate produced by gut flora. A major role of the propionate pathway is to provide succinate to the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle for energy production. The pathophysiology of these disorders is complex, involving both energy deprivation and accumulation of toxic organic acid intermediates that inhibit other pathways and cause cell death. MMA and PA are multi-organ system disorders in which chronic neurologic, cardiac, and renal involvement is punctuated by acute metabolic decompensations involving life-threatening metabolic acidosis and hyperammonemia. The standard of care for MMA and PA is a low protein diet, frequent feedings, and carnitine, which improves survival but does not prevent acute metabolic decompensations. Acute metabolic decompensations are additionally treated with intravenous fluids, high caloric intake, severe restriction or cessation of protein intake, and in severe cases, insulin and/or dialysis. Liver and/or kidney transplantation may be considered in patients with frequent metabolic decompensations or renal failure. There is a need for new treatments that can address the underlying disease pathophysiology and reach all affected organs. HST5040A is a small molecule drug that is being developed by HemoShear Therapeutics as an oral liquid formulation for patients with MMA and PA. The compound was discovered using a phenotypic screen based on the lowering of propionyl-CoA (P-CoA) in cultured primary hepatocytes obtained from the explanted livers of patients with MMA and PA undergoing transplantation. A key feature of the screening assay is HemoShear's REVEAL-Tx technology, which combines a 3-dimensional growth matrix with hemodynamic media flow to simulate the in vivo environment of liver sinusoids, thereby allowing cultured primary hepatocytes to be maintained in a differentiated state. HST5040 led to dose-dependent reductions in PCoA and its derived metabolites (2-methylcitric acid or MCA, propionyl-carnitine or C3, and 3-OH propionate) in MMA and PA hepatocytes, and additionally, methylmalonyl-CoA (M-CoA) and methylmalonic acid in MMA hepatocytes. The lowering of diseaserelated metabolites was accompanied by an increase in HST5040-CoA at a similar EC50, suggesting that HST5040 acts by redistributing the CoA pool away from toxic P-CoA and M-CoA metabolites. A combination of nonclinical data generated by HemoShear and clinical trial data generated by a previous sponsor in unrelated and discontinued indications supported the clearance of an Investigational New Drug application from the US FDA for HemoShear to initiate a Phase 2 clinical trial in patients with MMA and PA. The HERO study (Help Reduce Organic Acids) will enroll 12 subjects at least 2 years of age with MMA or PA (6 each) at up to 10 sites in the US in a 3-part study. Part A is a 5-month, open-label, within-patient, dose escalation study whose objective is to evaluate the safety, pharmacokinetics, pharmacodynamics and efficacy of 3 dose levels of HST5040 (1, 3, and 10 mg/kg) administered once daily po/pg to subjects with MMA and PA. Following a washout period, the same subjects will enter Part B, which is a 7-month, randomized, double-blind, placebo-control crossover study to evaluate the safety, pharmacokinetics, pharmaco dynamics, and efficacy of the optimal HST5040 dose from Part A. Subjects who complete Part B are eligible for Part C, which is an open-label extension study to evaluate the long-term safety and efficacy of HST5040. Part C may also enroll additional subjects with MMA caused by cobalamin A or B deficiencies or those with MMA or PA who are post-transplant and may benefit from HST5040. The main patient entry criteria include: age >2 years; diagnosis of MMA or PA with a history of metabolic decompensations and confirmed mutations in MMUT (Part A and B only) for MMA and PPCA or PCCB for PA; history of >= 1 acute metabolic decompensation, plasma NH3 >50 uM on two occasions, or plasma methylmalonic acid >150 uM within the past 2 years; plasma MCA >3x ULN; and a stable carnitine dose for 3 months. The primary efficacy endpoint of Part A and B is plasma MCA, a key biomarker in the causal pathway of both diseases. Secondary endpoints include other disease-related biomarkers, ureagenesis (Part B), oral intake, cardiac and renal function, frequency and duration of acute metabolic decompensations, neuropsychological functioning, quality of life, and Clinician and Caretaker/Patient Global Impressions of Change (CGI-C).Copyright 2021 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
