374. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 636652556
T1  - Face mask protective or trigger for exacerbation in COPD patients
T3  - 25th Congress of the Asian Pacific Society of Respirology, APSR 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Patil S. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Introduction: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) is a common, preventable and treatable disease that is characterised by persistent respiratory symptoms and airflow limitation that is due to airway and/or alveolar abnormalities usually caused by significant exposure to noxious particles or gases. In the ongoing pandemic of covid-19 doubts have been raised regarding the use of face-mask as it directly increases the resistance of the respiratory system. In this study we aim to evaluate the correlation between the use of facemark and development of hypercapnia in known COPD patients on medications. Aims and objectives: 1.To evaluate the relationship between face-mask and development of hypercapnia in COPD patients 2. To study the incidence of covid-19 in patients of COPD wearing face-mask Methodology: We included 100 patients of COPD on regular follow-up and treatment. The severity of COPD as per the GOLD guidelines was classified as GOLD B & GOLD C and only these categories of patients included. Patents were evaluated clinically at the time of follow-up and were advised to wear face-mask regularly. To ensure patients are wearing mask regularly when outside of their home, they were asked to tick on the chart which contained hourly time interval of 1 hour. Patient whenever outside home, needed to tick on the time interval and mask column and this ensured they were wearing mask regularly when outside home. After 4-6 weeks the patients were called for follow-up and evaluated for changes of CAT scores. DASI index was calculated in all study subjects. ABG was performed in those with exacerbation requiring hospitalisation. For other patients not in exacerbation, through physical examination was done. Invasive investigation of ABG was done only if symptomatic or physical examination s/o hypercapnia as explained by physical finding changes from start of the study to the end of the study period. RT-PCR for covid-19 of all the patients enrolled was done at the start of the study and in the end of the study. If symptomatic during the study period, rapid covid antigen test was done and RT-PCR for covid-19 was repeated. Inclusion criteria: Patients more than 20 years of age Patients known case of COPD on treatment Patients categorised as GOLD B and GOLD C Patients not vaccinated for covid-19 Patients wearing face-mask regularly Exclusion criteria: Patients not consenting for the study Patients with recent history of Myocardial infarction in past 3 months Patients infected with covid-19 and on treatment Patients with active tuberculosis and on treatment Results: Our study population was male dominated with 70% males and 30% females Average age group in our study population was 50+/-6 years (p value<0.01) Average CAT score on initial evaluation was 30+/-5 (p value<0.01) 5 patients had developed an episode of acute exacerbation of COPD during the time of study and required hospitalisation Average pCO2 levels in hospitalised patients was 70+/-5mmHg (p value<0.1) There was no significant change noted in CAT score post evaluation after 4-6 weeks with average CAT scores being 30+/-4 (p value<0.01) There was no change in physical quality of life as measured by DASI index Incidence of covid-19 was approximately 1% with only one study subject developing covid-19 during the study period All subjects enrolled for the study were wearing face mask for at least 6-8 hours/day on an average Conclusion(s): It can thus be conclusively said that face-mask does not cause hypercapnia in COPD patients provided proper techniques are followed in regards to wearing the mask and its washing/cleaning. Also the incidence of covid-19 is significantly lower in COPD patients wearing face-mask regularly.
