375. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 636645423
T1  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)
T3  - New Zealand Dermatological Society Incorporated Annual Meeting, NZDSI 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Milsom S. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is a heterogeneous disorder characterised by hyperandrogenism and chronic anovulation affecting between 6 and 13% of reproductive aged women. Symptoms of PCOS arise during the early pubertal years. However, the lack of internationally consistent criteria for diagnosis, assessment and management of PCOS has caused confusion for both women and clinicians. Recently, published and widely accepted PCOS guidelines (Teede, et al, Human Reproduction, September 2018) have made amajor contribution to clarity around the diagnosis and management of PCOS while identifying patient concerns and future research directions. In particular, the Rotterdam consensus has been universally supported for the diagnosis of adult women with PCOS, whereas caution has been recommended for the diagnosis of PCOS in adolescence, noting the overlap of symptoms of PCOSwith normal puberty and recommending stricter criteria. These guidelines support the role of the combined oral contraceptive as first linemanagement and provide context for the use of insulin sensitisers. The guidelines additionally highlight the impact of PCOS on mental health and focus on increasing support around education, lifestylemodification, emotional wellbeing and quality of life. Today's presentation will review the diagnosis and management of adolescent and adult PCOS incorporating the recommendations from the new PCOS guidelines. The presentation will focus on androgen excess symptoms rather than reproductive and metabolic consequences of PCOS. The role of new technology in ovarian ultrasound will be addressed.
