AN  - 2014627830
T1  - DIMINISHED OVARIAN RESERVE IN WOMEN WITH SICKLE CELL ANEMIA
T3  - 77th Scientific Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. Baltimore United States.
A1  - Pecker L.H.
A1  - Hussain S.
A1  - Lanzkron S.
A1  - Christianson M.S.
A1  - Mahesh J. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Objective: Young women with sickle cell anemia (SCA) may be at increased risk for DOR, but little is known about ovarian reserve or fertility in this population. Whether the primary SCA treatment, hydroxyurea (HU), a mild chemotherapeutic agent, is associated with DOR is not established; evidence is needed since females are started on potentially life-long therapy at 9-months of age. In this pilot study of ovarian reserve in women with SCA, the purposes were to (1) determine if antimullerian hormone (AMH) and antral follicle count (AFC) correlate, (2) compare AMH in age- and race-matched controls and, (3) study whether HU use is a risk for diminished ovarian reserve (DOR). Material(s) and Method(s): This prospective observational study included women 18 - 30 years old treated at an academic sickle cell center. Exclusion criteria included polycystic ovary syndrome and history of non-SCA related chemotherapy exposure. We measured ovarian reserve with AMH (Beckman Access Assay), FSH, estradiol and AFC by transabdominal or transvaginal ultrasound on menstrual cycle days 3-5 or randomly timed if on menses-suppressing contraception. Subjects' demographic, reproductive and SCA treatment history were obtained. Control data from age- and race-matched women with tubal factor infertility was obtained from an academic fertility center database. Result(s): Among 26 subjects, 16 were 19-25 years (median 22.5, IQR 21,24), 10 were 26 -30 years (median 28, IQR 27,29); 17 had both AFC and AMH performed. AMH correlated with AFC (Spearman's rho 0.49 (95% CI 0.40 - 0.94), p=0.03). Women with SCA ages 19-25 years had lower AMH than controls (median 2.11ng/mL (IQR 1.66, 4.446) vs 6.7 (IQR 6.2, 8.2), p=.043) but there was no difference between 26 - 30-year-olds (median 1.35ng/mL (IQR 1.0, 2.0) vs 2.0 (IQR 1.3, 3.2) p=0.11). DOR occurred in 1/16 subjects aged 19 - 25 years and 4 subjects aged 26 - 30 years. Compared to women without DOR (n=21), those with DOR (n=5) had lower AMH (0.93ng/mL vs 2.02, p<.01), higher FSH (11.3IU vs 6.75, p=.01), took HU (5/5 vs 10/21, p=.033) and had higher mean corpuscular volume (101.8fl vs 89, p<.01), a marker of HU adherence. There was no difference in AFC (7 follicles vs 12, p=0.23), disease complications (pain, acute chest syndrome, hospital admissions) by chart review nor or by patient report medical history score using the Adult Sickle Cell Quality of Life Measurement System (p>0.05). Conclusion(s): AMH and AFC are correlated in this previously unstudied population of women with disease- and treatment related risks to ovarian reserve. Young women with SCA have lower AMH than controls. DOR was not associated with markers of disease severity and occurred only in subjects taking HU with serologic evidence of adherence to treatment. No women had evidence of premature ovarian insufficiency. Impact Statement: Young women with SCA are at risk for DOR. HU use is a risk factor for DOR. This data raises questions about ovarian reserve counseling, testing, and indications for fertility preservation in women with SCA and forms the basis for ongoing study of the pathobiological mechanisms and clinical risks for andsignificance of DOR in women with SCA. References: Pecker, LH et al. Hydroxycarbamide and ovarian reserve in the Multicenter Study of Hydroxycarbamide. British Journal of Haematology. 2020. Elchuri, SV et al. The effects of hydroxyurea and bone marrow transplant on AMH levels in females with SCA. Blood Cells Mol Dis. 2015.Copyright © 2021
