385. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2014626311
T1  - OBSTRUCTIVE SLEEP APNEA RISK IS ASSOCIATED WITH LOWER HEALTH-RELATED QUALITY OF LIFE IN WOMEN WITH POLYCYSTIC OVARY SYNDROME
T3  - 77th Scientific Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. Baltimore United States.
A1  - Zhou X.P.
A1  - Morris J.R.
A1  - Shapiro M.
A1  - Jaswa E.G.
A1  - Cedars M.I.
A1  - Huddleston H.G. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Objective: Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) disproportionally affects women with polycystic ovary syndrome, with more than a third of patients impacted. Health-related quality of life (HRQoL) is an important metric of chronic disease, and women with PCOS have repeatedly been shown to experience lower HRQoL compared to the general population. A preliminary study revealed a relationship between an increased oxygen desaturation index on sleep studies and decreased HRQoL in women with PCOS, however the impact of OSA on HRQoL in this population remains poorly understood. Therefore, the objective of this study was to determine if being high-risk for OSA is associated with lower HRQoL. Material(s) and Method(s): All patients with a confirmed PCOS diagnosis by the Rotterdam criteria seen at a single university-based clinic between 2017-2021 were included. Participants completed validated questionnaires assessing OSA risk (Berlin) and HRQoL (Polycystic Ovary Syndrome Questionnaire, PCOSQ). The Berlin questionnaire consists of 3 categories related to OSA risk. A positive score in 2 or 3 categories is considered high-risk for OSA. The PCOSQ consists of 5 domains: emotions, body hair, weight, infertility, and menstrual problems. Lower PCOSQ scores indicate higher quality of life. Multivariate linear regression analyses were used to determine the mean PCOSQ score in each domain and overall in the high-risk versus low-risk OSA groups. The models were adjusted for age, body mass index (BMI), free testosterone level, insulin resistance as measured by the homeostatic model assessment of insulin resistance (HOMA-IR) score, depression symptoms as measured by the Patient Health Questionnaire-9 (PHQ-9) and anxiety symptoms as measured by the Generalized Anxiety Disorder-7 (GAD-7). Result(s): A total of 254 women with PCOS were included, of which 40.9% screened high-risk for OSA. The mean age of all participants was 27.1 years (SD 6.3) and mean BMI was 31.0 kg/m2 (SD 9.7). In the adjusted models, the high-risk OSA group had lower PCOSQ scores in the weight domain (6.0 vs. 6.8, p=0.004), emotions domain (5.0 vs. 5.6, p=0.009) and overall score (4.6 vs. 5.1, p=0.015) as compared to the low-risk OSA group. There were no differences in the PCOSQ scores in the menstrual problems, infertility and body hair domains between the high-risk and low-risk OSA groups. Conclusion(s): In our population of women with PCOS, those at high-risk for OSA experienced lower HRQoL in the weight and emotion domain on the PCOSQ, as well as a lower overall HRQoL score. These findings were independent of the effects of age, BMI, hyperandrogenemia, insulin resistance, and depression and anxiety symptoms. Impact Statement: OSA is a widely prevalent and likely underdiagnosed comorbidity in women with PCOS. This study suggests its impact on the important health outcome of HRQoL that has multidimensional consequences for the patient experience. Focus on identifying and treating OSA in this population has potential benefits beyond that for the condition alone.Copyright © 2021
