392. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 635307594
T1  - Effects of high flow nasal cannula (HFNC) on hospital admissions and health-related quality of life (HRQOL) measures in severe copd patients
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Theunisse C.
A1  - deGraaf N.
A1  - Vonk J.
A1  - Baart S.
A1  - Ponssen H.
A1  - Cheung D. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Rationale: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) is a disease with high morbidity and mortality worldwide. COPD exacerbations are one of the most important contributors to disease deterioration and decrease in health related quality of life (HRQoL). High Flow Nasal Cannula (HFNC) therapy is an innovative therapy that provides humidified and heated air through a nasal cannula. Although there is some preliminary evidence that HFNC is effective in COPD exacerbations, there are minimal data regarding the effectiveness of HFNC in stable severe COPD patients. The aim of the present study is to test the hypothesis that HFNC can decrease hospital admissions and improve HRQoL measures in severe COPD patients with frequent hospital admissions due to COPD exacerbations. Method(s): In a proof of concept prospective interventional multicenter study, 40 GOLD stage III and IV COPD patients with a high disease burden (> 2 exacerbations treated with antibiotics and/or corticosteroids) and > 1 hospital admission in the last year were included. Patients were given instructions on the usage of HFNC by a ventilation practitioner during a group session. Flow is 25-30 L/min and FiO2 is 21-35%. Outcome measures included hospital admissions, in hospital days, capillary pCO2, Medical Research Council dyspnea (MRC) score, Clinical COPD Questionnaire (CCQ) score and Hospital Anxiety Depression Scale (HADS) scores. Result(s): After 1 year 27 patients could be evaluated. Hospital admissions decreased by 0.96 admission (mean difference +/- SEM: 0.96 +/- 0.26; p = 0.001). In hospital days decreased by 7.22 days (7.22 +/- 1.78; p = 0.001). Capillary pCO2 decreased by 0.02 kPa (0.02 +/- 0.10; p = 0.85). The MRC dyspnea score decreased by 0.04 (0.04 +/- 0.16; p = 0.81). The CCQ score decreased by 0.06 (0.06 +/- 0.19; p = 0.76). The HADS anxiety score decreased by 0.63 (0.63 +/- 0.60; p = 0.31). The HADS depression score decreased by 0.32 (0.32 +/- 0.67; p = 0.64). Conclusion(s): One year HFNC therapy decreased hospital admissions and in hospital days without improving HRQoL measures significantly in severe COPD patients with high disease burden and frequent hospital admissions. Our findings support a prospective randomized controlled study examining the effects of HFNC in severe COPD patients with frequent hospital admissions.
