393. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 635307115
T1  - Respiratory symptoms and health perception improve rapidly in patients treated for pulmonary mycobacterium avium complex disease
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Henkle E.
A1  - Quittner A.L.
A1  - Brunton A.
A1  - Marras T.K.
A1  - Flume P.A.
A1  - Addrizzo-Harris D.J.
A1  - Ali J.
A1  - Philley J.
A1  - Winthrop K.L. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Rationale: Nontuberculous mycobacteria (NTM), primarily Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC), cause chronic, debilitating pulmonary disease. Patients and clinicians have reported that improvement in symptoms and healthrelated quality of life (HRQoL) are important outcomes of treatment. Our objective was to examine changes in symptoms and HRQoL during the first 6 months of treatment for pulmonary MAC disease. Method(s): The MAC2v3 study is a PCORI-funded randomized, multi-site pragmatic clinical trial. Patients are randomized to azithromycin and ethambutol +/- rifamycin. All meet ATS/IDSA disease criteria for pulmonary MAC, including two positive sputum cultures or a positive bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL), symptoms, and radiologic findings. Patients complete the NTM Symptom Module (4 domains) and QOL-Bronchiectasis (QOL-B, 8 domains plus bronchiectasis treatment burden) electronically at enrollment, and 1, 3, 6 months after treatment start; both are disease-specific, patient-reported outcome measures of HRQoL. Domain scores range from 0-100 (100=best, higher scores indicate better HRQoL). Here we report results for patients enrolled to date without distinguishing randomization group. We report baseline mean scores and compared mean score difference 0-3 and 0-6 months for each domain using a paired t-test. The minimal clinically important difference (MCID) was calculated by statistical methods: 1) SD of the baseline score and 2) 1 standard error of the measure (SEM) (change 0-6 months). Result(s): Among 68 included patients, 57 (84%) were female and 36 (53%) were >70 years of age. Overall 16 (24%) met case criteria with BAL only. Fifty-nine (89%) had a diagnosis of bronchiectasis, 8 (12%) chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, 17 (26%) asthma. At 6 months, Respiratory Symptoms improved 9.5 points (p<0.001, greater than either statistical MCID threshold, Health Perceptions 6.9 points (p=0.005), and Vitality 4.9 points (p=0.07) (Table). Overall there was no change in NTM Symptoms, but the n=28 (41%) with baseline scores <80 improved 6.6 points (p=0.05). Digestive Symptoms slightly worsened (-3.8, p=0.04, less than either MCID). No other domains had changed at 6 months (range -2 to +3). These patterns were consistently observed at 3 months. The MCID derived using statistical methods were relatively consistent for some domains (e.g. Respiratory Symptoms, NTM Symptoms, and Digestive Symptoms), but varied widely for others (Table). Conclusion(s): We observed significant improvements in overall Respiratory Symptoms and Health Perception scores, with improvement in NTM Symptoms only among those with lower baseline scores 6 months after initiating multi-drug therapy. MCIDs need to be established using anchor-based methods with more participants.
