396. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 635120375
T1  - Understandings of obesity complications, diagnosis and treatment in online communities: An IMI2 SOPHIA study
T3  - 28th European Congress on Obesity, ECO 2021. Online.
A1  - Kuruvilla S.
A1  - Farrell E.
A1  - Olholm Larsen Gronning M.
A1  - Hollmann E.
A1  - Le Roux C.W.
A1  - Nadglowski J.
A1  - Mc Gillicuddy D. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Introduction: Obesity is a complex chronic disease in which abnormal or excess body fat (adiposity) impairs health and quality of life, increases the risk of long-term medical complications and reduces lifespan [1]. While there are numerous messages about the causes and consequences of obesity, many people living with obesity struggle to find appropriate and accessible information, interventions and supports in the community[2]. This, combined with the stigma often faced by people with obesity [3], has resulted in many turning to online communities for information and support[ 4]. This 'netnographic' study aimed to examine how obesity is discussed in digital environments in order to understand people's reported experience of obesity complications, diagnosis and treatment. Method(s): A multi-method anthropological netnographic approach, combining qualitative and explorative analysis with quantitative analysis, was used in order to generate a better understanding of the online dialogue of people living with obesity. Key word searches in four languages generated a total of 570,110 posts on online forums, blogs and social media platforms. These were then analysed, grouped and tested to see if they could be quantified using multi-layer filtering. Result(s): Findings are presented in relation to online users' perceptions of obesity complications, diagnosis and treatment. Complications: * Diabetes and mental health difficulties emerged as the two leading obesity comorbidities mentioned * Stress was described in terms of being both a cause and a consequence of obesity * Obesity was perceived to be closely related to Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) and various cardiovascular diseases. Diagnosis: The most pertinent finding relating to diagnosis was that no relevant data regarding diagnosis could be extracted. This is believed to reflect the current landscape in which obesity is not officially recognised as a disease by many systems and also by many patients. Treatment: * Within dieting, low-carb diets were the preferred diet type for people living with obesity * Weight training (41%), running (31%) and walking (25%) were the most popular types of exercise mentioned online * The average sentiment around weight loss medications was positive (68.8%) * People who talk about weight loss surgery were happy with the outcomes of the procedure * Therapy (psychology) was viewed as a great support on the weight loss journey. Conclusion(s): A multi-method anthropological 'netnographic' approach is effective means of understanding people's experiences of living with obesity. Findings from this study offer an insight into perceptions of obesity complications, diagnosis and treatment options as reported in online communities.
