399. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634772943
T1  - Predictive markers of mortality and morbidity in the postoperative period of congenital heart surgery
T3  - 10th World Congress of the World Federation of Pediatric Intensive and Critical Care Societies, WFPICCS 2020. Virtual.
A1  - Hernandez M.
A1  - Rizzo J.
A1  - Maldonado D. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - AIMS & OBJECTIVES: Congenital Heart disease (CHD) occur in 8 out of 1,000 live births and are often lifethreatening. Surgical correction improves survival and quality of life. The objective of the study is to identify predictive markers of morbidity and mortality following surgical correction. METHOD(S): It is an observational, prospective and descriptive study with analytical component. During the last year, 214 children had open heart surgery at Roberto Gilbert Children Hospital in Guayaquil-Ecuador. We followed in arterial and venous blood gases the pH, pCO2, Sat and excess base at entrance to the Cardiovascular Intensive Care Unit (CVICU) and at 20 hours. Lactate was measured in the operating room, at CVICU admission and during postoperative period, to determine the time it remained elevated, its peak, and the rate of variation. In addition, the arteriovenous oxygen difference in oxygen saturation, its tissue extraction, the fraction of dead space and intrapulmonary shunt were also calculated. The survival rate and postoperative death rate were estimated and linked to various clinical and demographic variables. RESULT(S): Hospital mortality was equivalent to 6.5%. The variables that showed the highest predictive mortality value, beside weight and endotracheal intubation prior to surgery were extracorporeal time, age, inotropic score, lactate at admission and its peak. The multivariate analysis detected as independent mortality variables, maintained hyperglycemia and a hyperlacticaemia time of 48 hours. CONCLUSION(S): Maximum lactate elevation has a high predictive capacity to determine the risk of mortality and morbidity after pediatric heart surgery.
