AN  - 629635548
T1  - Adolescent Metabolic/Bariatric Surgery: Effects on Obesity, Comorbidities, and Insulin Resistance
T2  - Contemporary Endocrinology
A1  - Hsia D.S.
A1  - Shah A.S.
A1  - Inge T. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - The high prevalence of severe obesity and data demonstrating childhood obesity tracks into adulthood suggest that these adolescents are at high risk to develop obesity-related comorbidities-such as insulin resistance, type 2 diabetes, obstructive sleep apnea, polycystic ovarian syndrome, fatty liver disease, and cardiovascular disease-by young adulthood. Diet, exercise, and behavior modification have limited success in providing significant and durable weight loss, while pharmacological therapy is currently limited in the pediatric population. Metabolic/bariatric surgery (MBS) in the adolescent population is emerging as an effective long-term option, as it results in sustained weight loss and improves obesity-related comorbidities. This chapter will review common MBS procedures, the indications for use, and the effects of surgery on obesity, associated comorbidities, and insulin resistance in adolescents.Copyright © 2020, Springer Nature Switzerland AG.
