509. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634242420
T1  - Promise-MG-developing the patient-centered outcome
T3  - 67th American Association of Neuromuscular and Electrodiagnostic Medicine, AANEM 2020. Virtual.
A1  - Sanders D.
A1  - Narayanaswami P.
A1  - Guptill J.
A1  - Li F.
A1  - Desai R.
A1  - Venitz J.
A1  - Bibeau K.
A1  - Krueger A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Patient reported outcomes (PROs) assess outcomes that are important to patients; patients with the condition of interest must be engaged during the PRO development process. PROMISE-MG is a Patient Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) funded prospective, observational, comparative effectiveness study of immunosuppressants for myasthenia gravis (MG). OBJECTIVE(S): To describe the patient engagement process in developing the patient-centered primary outcome for PROMISE-MG. METHOD(S): Patients were actively engaged through: (1) a questionnaire survey of 58 patients at a national Myasthenia Gravis Foundation of America meeting, (2) a Web-based focus group of 13 patients, (3) a selection of the measure, and (4) an evaluation of the measure for completeness and accuracy by 30 patients describing their experiences with MG. RESULT(S): (1) Patient survey: Staying out of hospital was very important to 96% of respondents, living independently to 91.5%. Fewer/less frequent side-effects, fewer tablets/less frequent dosing, and less frequent physician visits/laboratory monitoring were very important to more than 33%. The most burdensome adverse effects were weight gain (43%), mood swings (36%), insomnia (34%), and diarrhea (30%). (2) Focus group: the word fatigue was most frequently associated with MG. Mobility limitations and visual and respiratory symptoms were most troublesome. Avoiding hospitalization was a high priority. Weight gain and longterm cancer risk were most concerning. (3) The MG-Quality of Life15r (MG-QOL15r) was identified as adequately capturing outcomes of importance to patients. (4) The MG-QOL15r was indicated by 29/30 MG patients as completely and accurately describing their experience with MG. SUMMARY/CONCLUSION: MG-QOL15r accurately and adequately reflects the patient voice and is the primary PRO for PROMISE-MG.
