523. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 632156902
T1  - Management of heavy menstrual bleeding in adolescence - The added value of a joint clinic
T3  - 13th Annual Congress of European Association for Haemophilia and Allied Disorders. The Hague Netherlands.
A1  - Tsimpanakos I.
A1  - Kadir R.A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Menstrual disorders are common in adolescent girls. Menstrual periods can be heavy and irregular; usually secondary to anovulatory cycles caused by the immaturity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis. Adolescent girls with inherited bleeding disorders are at a higher risk of heavy menstrual bleeding (HMB); often starting from menarche with a significant health implications such as anaemia, hospitalization and need for transfusion of blood or blood products. HMB has a negative impact on quality of life, can be a source of distress for adolescent girls and may affect their school attendance and performance as well as their social life. Management of HMB in adolescents is usually medical and there are several haemostatic and hormonal options that can be used singly or in combination. However, there are specific considerations when using these agents in adolescent girls that must be incorporated into a multidisciplinary and shared decision making with the girls and their family as well as the gynaecology and haematology teams. This is best provided in a joint clinic, where the experts can agree on optimal use of various treatments and assess these girls in one visit. Multi-disciplinary joint clinics can also provide the opportunity to extend management of these girls beyond the hospital, teaching and organizing home treatment for those who require regular factor replacement therapy and liaising with school or place of work when required. Girls and women with inherited bleeding disorders value provision of care in such model with high level of satisfaction and better compliance to treatment. This undoubtedly will lead to a better quality of care and life for these girls.
