A1  - Lowes B.
A1  - Espinoza J.
A1  - Blanco R.
A1  - Shen X.
A1  - Duffy C.
A1  - Hernandez A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background PARADIGM-HF showed that sacubitril/valsartan (sac/val) improved quality of life (QOL) vs enalapril in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), yet limited data are available regarding QOL changes after sac/val initiation in routine practice. Methods PROVIDE-HF was a prospective study of HFrEF outpatients initiated on sac/val vs controls with recent initiation/change in ACE/ARB dose at PCORnet centers (a national research network). Patients completed the Kansas City Cardiomyopathy Questionnaire (KCCQ) at baseline and weeks 2, 4, 8 and 12. Adjusted QOL change was estimated using inverse probability weighted models. The primary endpoint was KCCQ change through 12 weeks vs control. Other endpoints were responder analyses of >=5-pt and >=20-pt increase. Results Overall, 270 patients had both baseline and 12-week KCCQ data (151 sac/val; 119 control). The groups had similar demographics and HF details (median or %): 61 yr, 30% women, 25% black, EF 28%, NT-proBNP 1,083 pg/mL. Sac/val had a larger increase in KCCQ at 12 weeks vs control and were more likely to have a >=5-pt and >=20-pt response vs control (Table). Adjusted data demonstrated similar numerical improvements in the change in KCCQ and the 5-pt increase; the 20-pt increase remained significant (p=0.033). Conclusion In a prospective US study of HFrEF, sac/val initiation was associated with early improvements in QOL. Patients with sac/val initiation were more likely to have a large improvement in KCCQ (>20-pt) than with ACE/ARB. [Figure presented]Copyright © 2020 American College of Cardiology Foundation
