528. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2005202778
T1  - Session 414
T3  - 2020 AAGP Annual Meeting. Grand Hyatt San Antonio, San Antonio United States.
A1  - Roose S.
A1  - Karp J.
A1  - Lavretsky H. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - TRD is the norm, not the exception in older depressed adults, as most fail to remit with standard antidepressant pharmacotherapy. Understanding the benefits vs. risk of medication is crucial for this population, however, evidence from clinical trials comparing effectiveness and safety of pharmacological strategies in TRD older adults unresponsive is limited. The Optimum study, funded by PCORI, is a 5-center collaboration that will recruit 1500 patients over 60 with TRD. The OPTIMUM trial, study design in below diagram, will provide evidence on the comparative effectiveness of switching versus augmentation strategies. This trial will be conducted in the community, with patients receiving treatment from their own physicians, with decision support from the OPTIMUM team to guide them through the two-step algorithm. The investigators will also explore how aging-related factors affect the benefits and risks of different antidepressant strategies. This pivotal study will provide information that helps older adults get effective treatment while improving their quality of life and minimizing risks of medications. The study is now in its third year and has recruited over 660 patients. In this symposium the first presentation will be about the development of the study design, the choices that were made, processes for stakeholder engagement, challenges, and lessons learned in the early phases of OPTIMUM. The second presentation will present descriptive data on the subjects recruited to date. The last presentation will be an open discussion between the audience and the Optimum investigators with the particular focus on getting feedback from the clinicians treating TRD older patients on what they think can be learned form Optimum that would meaningfully inform their clinical practice.Copyright © 2020
