N2  - Background: Eosinophilic esophagitis (EoE) is an immune-mediated disease of the esophagus triggered by food and other antigens. The elimination of the six most common food allergens (milk, egg, wheat, soy, fish, and nuts) is highly effective at reducing symptoms and achieving histologic remission in EoE, but is difficult to implement and may negatively impact quality of life. Randomized trials evaluating the efficacy of less restrictive diets are lacking. We performed a multi-site prospective, randomized clinical trial to evaluate two less restrictive diets - the 1 - food (milk) elimination diet (1FED) versus the 4 - food (milk, egg, wheat, soy) elimination diet (4FED) - as assessed by symptom and quality of life instruments and histology. Method(s): Eligible children aged 6 to 17 years with histologically confirmed active EoE and symptoms of esophageal dysfunction were randomized to 1FED (n=38) and 4FED (n=25) over 10 sites. Patient reported outcomes and histologic data were collected at baseline and after 12 weeks of diet therapy. The primary efficacy endpoint was symptomatic improvement as measured by Pediatric EoE Symptom Score, v2.0. Secondary endpoints included the proportion of patients achieving histologic remission (peak eosinophil count < 15 eos/hpf), changes in histologic features (as measured by histology scoring system), and quality of life responses using the validated PROMIS and PedsQLTM 4.0 questionnaires. Result(s): Symptom scores were significantly improved from baseline after 1FED (p < 0.001) and 4FED (p < 0.001) treatments (Table 1). Change in total symptom score was greater in 4FED (-25.0 points) compared with 1FED (-14.3 points) (p=0.04). Histologic remission rates were similar between 1FED (44.1%) and 4FED (41.2%) (p=1.0). The severity and extent of histologic abnormalities significantly improved (decreased) in both treatment groups (1FED,-0.29, p < 0.001; 4FED, -0.25, p = 0.020), but were similar between groups (p=0.77). Clinically important improvements in psychosocial (p=0.01) and emotional well-being (anger, p=0.03; anxiety, p<0.01) scores were found in participants following the 1FED (Table 2). Conclusion(s): The less restrictive 1FED and 4FED achieved similar histologic improvements and remission rates (~40%) in this randomized clinical trial. Symptom scores improved in both treatment groups, but by a greater extent in 4FED. The 1FED had a generally positive impact on quality of life. For patients seeking improvement in symptoms and quality of life, a one food (milk) elimination diet should be considered a reasonable first treatment option. This study was funded through a Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) Award CER-1403-11593. The statements presented in this abstract are solely the responsibility of the author(s) and do not necessarily represent the views of PCORI or its Board. [Table Presented] [Table Presented]Copyright © 2019 European Association for the Study of the Liver. All rights reserved.
