622. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634458715
T1  - What drives patient's assessment of Quality of Life (QOL) among individuals with advanced Parkinson's disease (PD)?
T3  - 26th Annual Conference of the International Society for Quality of Life Research. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Fairclough D.
A1  - Sillau S.
A1  - Galifianakis N.B.
A1  - Katz M.
A1  - Miyasaki J.M.
A1  - Kluger B.M. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Aims: Goal: The goal of this exploratory analysis is to understand what drives the self-perception of QOL in individuals with PD. The data originated from an intervention study that had a secondary objective of validating and determining which of 4 commonly used QOL measures were most useful in assessing interventions in those with PD. Method(s): Methods: We recruited 210 PD patients with moderate to high palliative care needs across three sites. Inclusion criteria included a probable neurodegenerative cause of PD and moderate to high palliative care needs per the Palliative Care Needs Assessment Tool (PCNAT) modified for PD, however patients with urgent needs were excluded. The majority (76%) had mid-stage disease (Hoehn and Yahr stage 2 and 3) and the remainder were advanced stage (4 and 5). Duration of PS ranged from 8 months to 46 years (median-8 years). Assessments at baseline included the Parkinson Disease Questionnaire (PDQ 39), Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MOCA) McGill QOL Questionnaire, Promis 39, Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS), FACIT-Spiritual Well-Being (FACIT-SP) and Prolonged Grief Questionnaire (PG-12), The primary outcome for this analysis was the overall assessment of QOL by the patient from the McGill. The potential explanatory variables were measures of physical functioning/activities of daily living, pain, social well-being, cognition/fatigue, emotional well-being and existential well-being. R2 statistics were computed using simple linear regression of the patient's assessment of overall QOL on the measures of the various measures of the specific constructs (e.g. physical functioning). Result(s): The two components of explanatory factors which explained the greatest variation in the patient's overall assessment of their QOL were their emotional (R2 = 0.26) and spiritual well-being (R2 = 0.23). Social (R2 = 0.18) and cognition/fatigue (R2 = 0.17) followed. The weakest relationships in this population were physical functioning (R2 = 0.10) and pain (R2 = 0.07). Conclusion(s): Conclusion(s): Interventions that target QOL in individuals with PD should consider focusing on emotional and spiritual well-being, in addition to physical symptoms. Future work will include examining how these relationship change across stage of disease and over the duration of PD. This work was supported through a Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) Project Program Award IHS-1408-20134.
