625. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631603806
T1  - The efficacy of early detection bundle of COPD in Taiwan
T3  - 24th Congress of the Asian Pacific Society of Respirology. Hanoi Vietnam.
A1  - Lin C.-H.
A1  - Wang H.-C.
A1  - Cheng S.-L.
A1  - Lin M.-C.
A1  - Lin S.-H. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a leading cause of morbidity and mortality worldwide. Delayed diagnosis of COPD may lead to worse outcomes, missed opportunity for secondary prevention to improve long-term prognosis, an increased risk of developing other comorbidities, and subsequently impaired health status and increase in the cost of treatment. COPD early detection was recommended by GOLD guideline and may facilitate earlier intervention to slow the lung function decline, improve quality of life by decreasing symptoms and exacerbation frequency, and prevent progression of the disease. In previous studies, there are different approaches have been utilized for COPD early screening including questionnaire assessment and measurement of the handheld spirometer. However, even though several approaches have been developed and validated, the effectiveness of early detection of COPD in the Taiwanese has not been established. Our aim of this study is to evaluate the effectiveness of a COPD early detection bundle which comprised by COPD-PS questionnaire, portable spirometry, and Pcopd model. In our study, portable spirometry is useful tool for early detection using FEV1/FVC<0.74 and has better prediction accuracy for early detection of COPD than COPD-PS and Pcopd. Portable as a case-finding tool seems to be a feasible and simple alternative to conventional spirometry. Additionally, COPD-PS may be simple tool for screening high-risk population in the initial process to prevent inappropriate diagnosis even though our findings indicate that diagnostic capacity was low. Further, using FEV1/ FVC<0.74 from portable spirometry may optimize early referral for conventional spirometry and open an opportunity for early intervention to reduce the burden of COPD.
