627. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631393098
T1  - Comparison of physical fitness, reproductive status and quality of life in women with epilepsy on antiepileptic drugs
T3  - 33rd International Epilepsy Congress. Bangkok Thailand.
A1  - Pattnaik S.S.
A1  - Sarangi S.C.
A1  - Tripathi M.
A1  - Mahey R. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Purpose: This study aims to compare the physical fitness, reproductive status and quality-of-life (QOL) in women with epilepsy (WWE) on different antiepileptic drugs (AEDs). Method(s): This cross-sectional study included WWE who were on AEDs for > 3 months. Physical fitness was assessed by using International Physical Activity Questionnaires (IPAQ) and body composition analysis. Subjects were interviewed for menstrual abnormalities. Validated questionnaires were used for assessment of Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) (Clinical tool for diagnosis of PCOS), hirsutism (modified Ferriman-Gallwey scale), QOL (QOLIE-10) and Stigma in epilepsy (Epilepsy Stigma Scale). These parameters were compared between WWE based on demographic and seizure characteristics along with AED treatment regimen i.e. amonotherapy vs. polytherapy; and b-conventional vs. newer AEDs. Result(s): A total 181 WWE with mean age of 26.7 +/- 7.2 years on treatment with AEDs (conventional: carbamazepine, phenytoin and valproate; and newer: clobazam, lamotrigine, levetiracetam, oxcarbazepine) were enrolled. WWE on monotherapy (n = 89) were associated with more physical activity (p = 0.040), less PCOS (7.86 vs. 22.82%,p = 0.005) than polytherapy; but no significant difference in association of menstrual abnormalities and hirsutism. Body composition(BMI, fat percentage, fat mass, water percentage, fat-free-mass, muscle mass, bone mass), QOLIE-10 score and stigma prevalence were found to be similar in between mono and polytherapy WWE. Newer and conventional AEDs groups showed similar trend of body composition, reproductive, QOL abnormalities and stigma prevalence; except, conventional AEDs group being physically more active (p = 0.023). Though WWE > 35 years and married women had higher physical activity because of household work, still they had higher fat percentage(p<0.001), fat mass(p<0.001), and less water percentage(p = 0.011) than younger (18-35 years) and unmarried WWE. Conclusion(s): Physical inactivity was commonly associated with WWE on polytherapy and newer AEDs; reproductive abnormalities were also common among polytherapy group. So further studies with intervention strategies to increase physical activities and their effect on reproductive abnormalities in WWE needs investigation.
