628. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630916578
T1  - Study of clinical presentation and predictors of adverse outcome in patients admitted for acute exacerbation of COPD
T3  - 29th International Congress of the European Respiratory Society, ERS. Madrid Spain.
A1  - Maheshwari P. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction: COPD - Common preventable and treatable disease that is characterized by persistent respiratory symptoms and airflow limitation that is due to airway and/or alveolar abnormalities usually caused by significant exposure to noxious particles or gases. Aecopd: an acute worsening of the patient's condition from the stable state, which is sustained and may warrant the patient to seek additional treatment. AE-COPD alters the quality of life including mortality and morbidity & causes a great socioeconomic burden. There are some factors or predictors associated with the AE-COPD like Age, disease duration, associated comorbidities etc. that not only help us to guide the management of the disease per-se but they also decide the fate or the probable outcome of the disease at some extent. Our Aim: correlate these predictors & the probable outcome. Material(s) and Method(s): After fulfilling the inclusion and exclusion criteria, we thoroughly examined the consecutive 100 in-patients of AECOPD, treated them as per AECOPD management protocol with some special as needed treatment like NIV, IMV, NRBM, ICD etc. and assessment of the predefined composite outcome done. Our outcome were grouped as adverse outcome which includes RCU/ICU admission, Need of NIPPV/IMV, Prolonged hospitalization(>11Days), Re-admission(with in 1 month) and Death. While good outcome was the absence of the entire above-mentioned adverse outcome. Result(s): Summarized in figures. (Figure Presented) Conclusion(s): Advance age, High pCO2 and Low levels of pO2, Serum sodium, Serum albumin & GCS was associated with more adverse outcome BUT some can be modifiable at home so alters the outcome & help us to priorities our Treatment.
