630. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630355264
T1  - Surgical management of tracheal stenosis in an adult patient with Jarcho Levine syndrome
T3  - 2019 International Conference of the American Thoracic Society , ATS 2019. Dallas, TX United States.
A1  - Kwon M.
A1  - Arunthari V.
A1  - Leventhal J.P.
A1  - Hakaim A.
A1  - Yeager T.
A1  - Thomas M. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Jarcho Levine syndrome (JLS) (synonym, spondylocostal dysostosis) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by vertebral and rib anomalies leading to restrictive respiratory physiology. A 36-year-old female with JLS presented with worsening dyspnea of 3 years duration. Her congenital vertebral deformities and abnormal growth progressed over time, eventually causing short stature and severe shortening of the trunk. Despite this severe deformity, she was able to work full time but noticed increasing breathing difficulty with even mild effort. She was already receiving nightly positive airway pressure therapy. On exam, her oxygen saturation was 95% on room air at rest. Pulmonary function tests showed a total lung capacity of 1.76 liters (59% of predicted) and vital capacity of 650ml (27% of predicted); 6-minute walk distance was 244 meters. Arterial blood gas showed daytime hypercapnia (pCO2, 61.9 mmHg on room air). CT angiography of the chest revealed a focal narrowing of the trachea at the thoracic inlet with 50% reduction in cross-sectional area, secondary to an indentation caused by the right brachiocephalic artery being compressed between the spine and manubrium. A surgical bony decompression was recommended to relieve tracheal stenosis and if this was ineffective, then tracheal resection and reconstruction were planned. Resection of right hemi-manubrium, sternoclavicular joint and head of the first rib with mobilization of the right brachiocephalic artery and suspension arteriopexy was performed uneventfully. Intraoperative bronchoscopic exam after bony decompression showed the tracheal stenosis to have resolved and the lumen was noted to be much wider. She was extubated in the operating room, and required supplemental oxygen by nasal cannula initially. Two months after surgery her dyspnea improved and she returned to work. Most reported cases of JLS have been in the neonatal or pediatric age groups. Respiratory compromise in JLS stems from underdeveloped or maldeveloped vertebrae and ribs, leading to severely reduced size of thorax and inability to support ventilatory demand (thoracic insufficiency syndrome). Reported treatment options for pediatric patients include expandable prosthetic titanium ribs to promote the growth of spine. Unlike most patients with JLS, our patient was able to maintain normal physical function and quality of life until she developed dyspnea in her 4th decade of life. To our knowledge, this is the first report where successful surgical management of tracheal stenosis in JLS was performed, resulting in at least moderate symptomatic relief of dyspnea.
