N2  - RATIONALE: Chicago has some of the highest morbidity and mortality rates attributable to asthma in the U.S., making asthma a priority to the city's health department. CAPriCORN is a PCORnet Clinical Data Research Network (CDRN) comprised of a diverse set of health organizations throughout Chicago aiming to build an infrastructure for multi-site clinical trials and to characterize patients with chronic health conditions such as asthma. The present study aims to evaluate current demographic and health characteristics associated with asthma control across eight CAPriCORN sites. METHOD(S): Adults with asthma (>=18 years old) were identified through electronic medical records (EMRs) at each site using a validated computable phenotype for asthma (1). Potential participants were recruited by mail or in-person when attending outpatient appointments with their asthma specialist or primary care provider. Participants were consented and asked to complete a questionnaire that obtained demographic and patient-reported outcomes including asthma health status. Bivariate analysis was performed to assess differences between poor and adequate asthma control. Poor control was defined a priori with a mean cutoff of 1.5 from the Asthma Control Questionnaire. RESULT(S): Among 318 enrolled participants, the majority were female (75%), two-thirds (62%) had at least some college education, and 50% and 15% of respondents self-identified as black race and Hispanic ethnicity, respectively. Poorly controlled asthma comprised 42% (n=134) of the cohort. Among those with poorly-controlled asthma, a greater proportion were under-represented minorities (79% vs. 59%; p=0.002) and had at least some college education (53% vs. 78%; p<0.01). Quality of life (p<0.01), physical health (p<0.01), and mental health were worse (p<0.01). More specifically, patients with poorlycontrolled asthma more frequently reported being depressed often or always in the prior seven days (11% vs. 4%, p<0.01). For asthma care, a greater proportion of exacerbations occurred in the poorly-controlled group with 75% requiring oral steroid prescriptions vs. 48% (p<0.01) and 98% reporting increased use of a rescue inhaler vs. 87% (p<0.01). No differences in controller medications were noted between the groups. Fewer poorly controlled respondents had allergy testing (73% vs. 87%; p=0.02) or good sleep quality in the past 7 days (26% vs. 53%; p<0.01). CONCLUSION(S): In this Chicago-based multi-organization study, patients with poorly-controlled asthma fared worse on nearly all measures of quality of life, physical health, and mental health. Furthermore, disparities in diagnostics and medication use are apparent. Our findings highlight opportunities to intervene and improve asthma control and potentially reduce disparities in health outcomes.
