634. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2004231019
T1  - Repurposing Levodopa in healthy older adults to enhance slow wave sleep with potential to modify disease progression in Alzheimer's disease
T3  - 15th World Sleep Congress. Vancouver Canada.
A1  - Coulthard E.
A1  - Carr W.
A1  - Averill G.
A1  - Radtke O.
A1  - Selwood J.
A1  - Williams R.
A1  - Ford E.
A1  - Wearn A.
A1  - McErlane J.
A1  - Bartsch U.
A1  - Durant C.
A1  - Grogan J.
A1  - Isotalus H. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction: Over 50 million people live with dementia globally at an estimated annual cost of US$3 trillion. Treatments directly targeting the primary pathologies in Alzheimer's disease - amyloid and tau - have so far proved ineffective. New therapeutic strategies are desperately needed. The most promising strategy seems to be targeting early stages of the disease, perhaps even before obvious symptoms emerge. Sleep affects quality of life and cognition in dementia and recent data suggest that toxins such as amyloid are filtered from the brain during slow wave sleep. Therefore, enhancing slow wave sleep is a novel target for disease modification in Alzheimer's disease. Our previous work in patients with Parkinson's demonstrated that dopamine-like medication enhanced overnight memory during sleep. Here we tested the hypothesis that Levodopa, a standard Parkinson's medication converted to dopamine in the central nervous system, improves memory and sleep in healthy older people. Material(s) and Method(s): 35 healthy older adults (mean age 68.9, SD 3.5) consented to a double-blind, placebo-controlled, crossover, treatment-order randomised, single-dose clinical trial of nocturnal levodopa in our sleep laboratories with Medical Research Ethics Committee and Medicines and Healthcare Regulation Authority approvals. 150 minutes before usual bedtime, all participants were administered the peripheral antiemetic domperidone. 30 minutes later, participants received either Levodopa (Co-beneldopa controlled release 200/50mg) or placebo. In a computerised memory task, participants learned 80 words before taking medications and were tested on a subset (20) of the words 30 minutes after taking levodopa/placebo and then on the same subset and a new subset (20) the next morning. 12 channel polysomnography was used to measure EEG, eye movements, myography and electrocardiography overnight. In the morning participants completed the St Mary's Hospital Sleep and the Leeds Sleep Evaluation Questionnaires. Sleep stages were scored manually by an expert scorer with double checking of 10% using standard AASM criteria. Using the signal acquired at electrode Cz only, we automatically detected spindle events during N2 and N3 sleep using a custom MATLAB algorithm. From all detected events we calculated mean spindle characteristics (amplitude, duration, frequency and density). To determine the effect of dopamine on sleep architecture, we performed pairwise comparisons between the levodopa and placebo nights, corrected for multiple comparisons. Linear mixed models were used to assess the effect of levodopa on memory performance. Result(s): Levodopa increased the total amount of N3 sleep by around 11% (pcorrected=0.044) and increased spindle amplitude (pcorrected=0.008). There were no effects on other sleeps stages, total sleep duration or subjective measures of sleep. Levodopa augmented the bias towards remembering salient information tagged as important by repetition and forgetting unimportant information (p=0.018). Conclusion(s): Levodopa is a safe, well-tolerated drug that increased the duration of deep non-REM sleep opening up a potential avenue for trials to assess whether levodopa might delay progression to dementia and improve quality of life. Levodopa also had a behaviourally helpful effect on memory retention. Acknowledgements: This work was funded by the Medical Research Council, BRACE charity and the David Telling Charitable Trust.Copyright © 2019
