635. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630056488
T1  - Insomnia in medical students: Review of the literature
T3  - 2018 Brazilian Sleep Society Meeting. Criciuma Brazil.
A1  - Cardoso G.M.S.
A1  - Correa C.C.
A1  - Weber S.A.T. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction: Medical Students are more exposed to contributing factors to develop sleep disorders, like insomnia. Insomnia is defned as the diffculty to start, to maintain or return to sleep. Aim(s): To analyze the frequency of insomnia in medical students and associating factors, reported in literature. Method(s): We realized a search strategy with the key words Insomnia/Students/ Medicine at the data sets BIREME and Pubmed. We included studies of clinical research, reporting central thematic of insomnia in medical students. Review studies were excluded. Result(s): We localized 33 studies in BIREME and 140 studies in Pubmed. After excluding studies (reviews, repeated and out of scope), 14 studies met the inclusion criteria. All studies reported application of several questionnaires on medical students. The period of publication ranged from 2001 to 2018, being originated in United States, Colombia, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Taiwan, Serbia, Brazil, Costa Rica, Mexico and Cuba. The frequency of insomnia varied from 33% a 93%, being more frequent as mild insomnia. It was more prevalent in the female gender, in students who live in noisy places, who do an excessive use of cellphones and who study and work. Insomnia was also associated with going to bed on average time at 1h53 a.m., high levels of stress, anxiety, depression, alcohol and sleeping pills consumption, cognitive hyperactivity, hypervigilance, pressure, emotional frustration and with underlying diseases that are migraine, gastritis, asthma, rhinitis, polycystic ovaries, gastric ulcer, ulcerative colitis, hypothyroidism and fbromyalgia. As protective factors, insomnia occurred less in students who practice physical activities. Conclusion(s): Medical students are a population with high prevalence of sleep privation, related with rising academic exigency and extensive course load, leading to insomnia, fatigue and excessive daily somnolence. There is an urgent need to implement more actions in under graduation and graduation, in order to integrate adequate hygiene and sleep quality, as it implicates in worsening of quality of life, drop in academic achievement and learning, mental health problems and high levels of stress.
