639. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2002982896
T1  - DEMOGRAPHICS AND CLINICAL PROFILE OF SEVERE COPD PATIENTS WITH STABLE CHRONIC HYPERCAPNIC RESPIRATORY FAILURE STARTED ON HOME NONINVASIVE VENTILATION BY PRIMARY CARE PHYSICIANS
T3  - CHEST 2019 Annual Meeting. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Qasim N.
A1  - Duree V.
A1  - Zaidi N. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - SESSION TITLE: Identifying Successes and Failures of NIV and Airway Clearance: From COPD to Neuromuscular Disease SESSION TYPE: Original Investigations PRESENTED ON: 10/21/2019 1:30 PM - 2:30 PM PURPOSE: In severe COPD patients with stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure, long term use of home non-invasive ventilation (NIV) has been shown to improve survival, exercise capacity, blood gases and health-related quality of life. Additionally, NIV may be associated with fewer hospital admissions and lower treatment costs. Although primary care physicians play a critical role in the screening, diagnosis and treatment of COPD, it is commonly thought that home NIV for severe COPD patients is initiated only by pulmonary specialists. The purpose of this study was to document the demographics and clinical profile of severe COPD patients with stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure started on home NIV by their primary care physicians. METHOD(S): We performed a retrospective review of all severe COPD patients with stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure from 2014 to 2018 who were referred by their primary care physicians to VieMed, a national durable medical equipment (DME) company in the United States, for home NIV in a community setting in the Midwest region. RESULT(S): There were 14 subjects, 9 men, 5 women, with a mean age of 67 years, age range 36-82 years. All had severe COPD and stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure. Their mean PCO2 was 68 mmHg (PCO2 range 53-109 mmHg), mean weight 220 lbs, weight range 130-391 lbs, mean height 69 inches, height range 63-76 inches. All were on long term oxygen supplementation. All were set up on NIV at home by certified respiratory therapists employed by the DME company. The NIV settings were determined by the certified respiratory therapists. During the study period, NIV was well tolerated and all patients remained compliant with therapy. No complications were noted and none of these patients required referral to a pulmonary specialist. CONCLUSION(S): This group of severe COPD patients with stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure was safely initiated on home NIV by their primary care physicians in consultation with certified respiratory therapists in a community setting. These patients remained compliant with NIV therapy, had no complications and did not require referral to a pulmonary specialist. CLINICAL IMPLICATIONS: Primary care physicians may initiate home NIV for their severe COPD patients with stable chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure. This should be done in consultation with a certified respiratory therapist and may not need referral to a pulmonologist. DISCLOSURES: No relevant relationships by Valarie Duree, source=Web Response No relevant relationships by Naurez Qasim, source=Web Response No relevant relationships by Navid Zaidi, source=Web ResponseCopyright © 2019 American College of Chest Physicians
