649. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 627698165
T1  - The emergency department-initiated noninvasive ventilation for acute respiratory failure patients with do-not-resuscitate order
T3  - Society for Academic Emergency Medicine Annual Meeting, SAEM 2019. Las Vegas, NV United States.
A1  - Yen D.H.-T.
A1  - Chiu J.-Y. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Little is known about the role of different oxygen provisions in palliative care patients in the emergency department (ED). The purpose of this study is to investigate the effect of emergency department-initiated noninvasive ventilation devices (NIV) for acute respiratory failure (ARF) patients with do-notresuscitate (DNR). Method(s): We conducted a prospectively registered and retrospective analysis study in a tertiary medical center from June 1, 2017 to December 31 2017. Patients met one of the criteria of ARF will be enrolled. The ARF defined as following, hypercapnia means PaCO2 > 45 mm Hg or pH < 7.35; hypoxia : (PaO2)/(FiO2) (PF ratio) <= 300. Patients were categorized to NIV group and oxygen group. The decision of using NIV or oxygen only was up to the emergency physician who was in charge of the patients. We compared the clinical characteristics, respiratory parameters, and outcomes between two groups. The primary outcome was in-hospital mortality. The secondary outcome was the improvement of respiratory parameters, including pH, PaO2, PCO2, HCO3, and PF ratio within 48 hours of hospital admission. Result(s): A total of 282 patients recruited with 112 in NIV group and 170 in oxygen group. The mean age was 82.6 +/- 12.6 years, and 61.7% was male. The NIV group improved much better in pH, PaCO2, HCO3, and PF ratio, respectively, than those of oxygen group (p < 0.05). No statistical significance in the ICU [21.4% vs. 15.3%, p=0.187] and in-hospital [46.4% vs. 44.1%, p=0.703] mortality between two groups, respectively. In regression analysis, PaCO2 (OR 1.07 95% CI 1.04-1.11), acute kidney injury (OR 4.79 95% CI 1.69-13.58), and chronic renal disease (OR 1.75 95% CI 1.12-2.74) at the time of hospital admission were associated with NIV use. Conclusion(s): Our study results demonstrated that NIV, initiated in the ED, is an effective treatment for physiological improvements for ARF patients with DNR. Further assessment of the impact on quality of life among these patients would be mandatory.
