650. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001868830
T1  - No difference in quality of life or depression/anxiety diagnosis between middle-aged women with PCOS and age-matched controls
T3  - EMAS Congress 2019. Berlin Germany.
A1  - Forslund M.
A1  - Landin-Wilhelmsen K.
A1  - Krantz E.
A1  - Trimpou P.
A1  - Schmidt J.
A1  - Brannstrom M.
A1  - Dahlgren E. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Objective: Several studies show that women with Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)in fertile age have decreased Health-Related Quality of Life (HRQoL)and a higher proportion of mood disorders than women in general. The aim of this study was to determine whether these differences in HRQoL and the prevalence of psychiatric disorders remained in peri- and postmenopausal women with Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Method(s): Women with PCOS (n = 27)were diagnosed in 1992 and included in a follow up study in 2016. Randomly selected, age-matched women (n = 94)from the World Health Organization MONItoring of trends and determinants for CArdiovascular disease (WHO MONICA-GOT)2008, aged 38-68, served as controls. Mean age of the study participants was 52 years. Structured interviews and Short Form (SF)-36 questionnaires were used and clinical examinations were performed. Current diagnosis of depression and anxiety was noted, as well as current use of psychopharmacological medications. Result(s): No differences in SF-36 scores were found, neither in physical nor mental component summaries. No association was seen between PCOS diagnosis and depression/anxiety (adjusted OR 1.6, CI 0.5-5.7). There was no difference in proportion of use of psychopharmacological medications (22% versus 22%, p = 1.00). Nulliparity was significantly associated with depression/anxiety, adjusted OR = 4.7 (CI 1.6-13.9), irrespective of PCOS diagnosis. Conclusion(s): The differences seen between women with and without PCOS regarding HRQoL and depression/anxiety does not persist in peri- and post-menopausal aged women. The odds for depression/anxiety was 4.7 times higher if the woman was nulliparous, compared to the women who had given birth, regardless of a PCOS diagnosis.Copyright © 2019
