651. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 627465667
T1  - Prostate cancer outcome registry - Australia and New Zealand (Vic) and TrueNTH Australia feasibility study
T3  - 2019 Biennial Meeting of the Asia Pacific Society of Sexual Medicine. Brisbane, QLD Australia.
A1  - Cowan D. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction & Objectives: Men often self-reported poor quality of life when contacted for routine follow up by the Prostate Cancer Outcome Registry-Victoria (PCOr-Vic) 12 months after treatment. Data from the PCOR- Vic registry have identified that one in three men will self-report moderate to big problems with their sexual function 12 months after treatment; 9% will report moderate to big urinary problems and 9% will have persistent bowel problems 12 months after initiating radiotherapy. These are known side effects of treatment but carry a significant burden to men and their partners. While the registry provided reports back to clinicians, there was a desire to facilitate some intervention to assist men. Method(s): The Registry contacts men from the Gippsland and Barwon regions who are 12 months post completion of (Table presented) treatment and administers the EPIC-26. Men who report moderate to big bother with any of the domains of the EPIC-26 are invited to participate in the TrueNTH project. Consented men are referred to TrueNTH where a nurse care coordinator contacts them and consults with them to discuss any identified bother or unmet need. The TrueNTH care coordinator proposes a care plan to manage the man's bother and informs the treating medical specialist of the proposed plan. Once agreed, the TrueNTH care coordinator implements the care plan. We implemented the TrueNTH Care Coordination project. Result(s): A total of 17 men from Gippsland region and 19 men from Barwon region respectively were followed up at 24 months, 12 months post receiving the TrueNTH intervention. Men who reported bother with sexual function at 12 months post completion treatment who received the TrueNTH intervention were associated with a 62% lower risk of reporting moderate to severe sexual problems at 24 months when compared to normal practice. Conclusion(s): Care coordination can assist men. While it is important to involve the patient's treating clinician, this can cause delay in recruitment. A population-based registry can deliver a coordinated quality improvement activity via telephone which is accessible to most men, and has been shown to positively impact quality of life.
