652. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 627465235
T1  - Examining completeness and agreement of comorbidity data obtained from administrative data, medical records and self-reports by men diagnosed with prostate cancer undergoing radical prostatectomy
T3  - 2019 Annual Scientific Meeting of the Urological Society of Australia and New Zealand. Brisbane, QLD Australia.
A1  - Sheriffdeen A.
A1  - Millar J.
A1  - Martin C.
A1  - Evans M.
A1  - Tikellis G.
A1  - Evans S. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction and Objectives: The Prostate Cancer Outcomes Registry- Australia and New Zealand (PCOR-ANZ) is a binational registry that collects information pertaining to the treatments, procedures, interventions and quality of life for prostate cancer patients following diagnosis. There is uncertainty as to whether comorbidities should be adjusted for when reporting on prostate cancer specific mortality (PCSM) rates, given that only National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) risk group is used in the risk prediction model. In this study we investigate the extent to which there is concordance in capture of comorbidities in men with prostate cancer who have undergone a radical prostatectomy, using three data sources: 1 the Charlson Comorbidity Index (CCI) derived from administrative International Classification of Diseases-version 10 Australian modified (ICD-10AM) coding data 2 a patient self-reported comorbidity survey that collects data on a subset of 8 comorbidities also captured by the CCI. 3 medical record review. Method(s): Six hospitals contributing to PCOR-Vic were recruited. The ICD-10AM comorbidity codes for men undergoing a radical prostatectomy between January 2017 and April 2018 were collected. Medical records were reviewed to manually extract comorbidities used to generate the CCI. The self-reported comorbidity survey was distributed through PCOR-Vic to eligible men. Kappa, prevalence-adjusted bias-adjusted kappa (PABAK) and Gwet's AC1 coefficients were used to quantify the concordance between the three sources of comorbidity data. Result(s): Of the 217 eligible participants, 122 (56%) responded to the survey. The percentage agreement between the administrative data, medical records and selfreports was between 92% and 99%, and the PABAK coefficient between 0.83 and 0.98 for all conditions aside from cancer, suggesting a strong to almost perfect agreement for most conditions. The range of Gwet's AC1 coefficient scores was between 0.91 and 0.99, for all conditions except cancer. Conclusion(s): There was strong to almost perfect agreement for seven of the eight comorbidities captured across the three data sources, when assumptions were made as to the seriousness of the condition in the patient-reported survey. The exception was the cancer comorbidity, which was under-reported in the patientreported survey. Administration of the survey to patients before surgery may address this discordance.
