A1  - Wilmot M.-C.
A1  - Setterfield J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - A 36-year-old woman presented with a 5-year history of pain, itching and fissuring affecting her vulval skin with considerable reduction in her quality of life. A previous skin biopsy performed elsewhere in 2012 was reported to show secondary changes following excoriation. Viral, bacterial and fungal swabs were reported as negative. She had a history of polycystic ovarian syndrome, eczema, depression, anxiety, asthma and vitiligo. Physical examination revealed macerated skin in the crurae and labia majora. A vulval biopsy from the right labia majora showed an area of epidermal acantholysis. At high power the classical dilapidated brick wall appearance of the acantholytic keratinocytes was evident. Immunofluorescence studies were negative. A clinicopathologic diagnosis of Hailey-Hailey disease (HHD) was made. HHD is a rare autosomal dominant genodermatosis caused by loss-of-function mutations in the ATP2C1 gene.1 A mutation in ATP2C1 causes a loss of keratinocyte adhesion, which in HHD classically manifests in the third or fourth decade with symmetrical flaccid vesicles or plaques affecting flexural sites. There have been just twelve reported cases of HHD confined to the vulva. In the majority there was a delay in the diagnosis which was likely to have been be due to its low incidence and the variety in clinical morphology (from verrucous to eroded plaques or papules). She was initially diagnosed and managed as a case of lichen simplex chronicus until a skin biopsy showed classic features of HHD. In terms of treatment, patients should be advised to seek prompt treatment of inflammation and secondary infections. Evidence of efficacy for topical and systemic therapies (such as antibiotic, corticosteroid preparations, calcineurin inhibitors, cyclosporine, acitretin and methotrexate) is limited to reports of single cases or small case series. Importantly, there are anecdotal reports of squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) arising in vulvar and penile lesions of HHD. It is unclear whether the chronic impairment of the epidermal barrier in HHD increases the risk of infection from oncogenic strains of human papilloma virus or whether ATP2C1 mutations themselves cause a genetic predisposition to cancer. Our patient's symptoms failed to improve with topical clobetasol alone. A repeated vulval swab was positive for pseudomonas, staphylococcus and coliforms. The patient was treated with a 2-month course of an oral tetracycline antibiotic followed by clobetasone butyrate 0.05%, nystatin, and oxytetracycline and then mupirocin 2%, and a clinical improvement was noted.Copyright © 2018
