766. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 625667318
T1  - Use of transcutaneous carbon dioxide values for improving compliance and effectiveness of noninvasive ventilation in individuals with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis
T3  - 29th International Symposium on ALS/MND. Glasgow United Kingdom.
A1  - Isaacs A.E.
A1  - Hayes H.
A1  - Leatham J.
A1  - Bromberg M.
A1  - Brown J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Background: Quality of life and survival are improved with noninvasive ventilation (NIV) in patients with ALS (1). Additionally, early start of NIV has been shown to reduce respiratory decline (2). Compliance is often a challenge. Providing the patient with the full picture of respiratory compromise, including pCO2 values may be helpful. Practice is typically limited in providing pCO2 values because it is traditionally obtained by an arterial blood gas, which is invasive, expensive, and results are delayed. Transcutaneous Carbon Dioxide (TCO2) Monitoring has been shown to accurately predict pCO2 (3). It is noninvasive, painless, and more cost effective and efficient. Objective(s): To determine if providing more information to the patient about respiratory compromise using TCO2 would improve compliance with NIV. Method(s): Forty-five patients were recommended to use NIV based on standard guidelines of respiratory compromise. They were provided additional information about their pCO2 levels, via TCO2 when NIV was recommended. Demographic data; gender, age, months since diagnosis, and ALS FRS Respiratory subscale were captured. We report the number of individuals using NIV, the number of hours used, pCO2 values, and Oxygen saturation values (O2), FVC and NIF measurements. Result(s): Eighteen males (40%) and twenty seven females (60%) were evaluated with a mean age of 61.5 years (range 42.2 to 81.5), 27.3 months since diagnosis, and mean ALS FRS 7.3. Thirty one individuals (69%) chose to use NIV with the average time for use was 12 hours, one used their NIV56 (4 hours) in a 24 hour period and six used NIV 423 hours. Fourteen individuals (31%) chose not to use NIV. Mean TCO2 was 43mmHg (range 31-81), five had TCO2535mmHg, twelve had TCO2445mmHg. Patients with high TCO2 had their NIV adjusted to compensate and/or were educated to use their NIV more frequently. Three persons with TCO2445mmHg chose not to use NIV. No correlation between TCO2 and NIF or TCO2 and FVC was observed in this cohort. Discussion and conclusions: Providing additional information about pCO2 values to the patient and provider may aid in compliance with NIV. Identifying ways to improve compliance is warranted for improving quality of life and decreased respiratory decline.
