769. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 624607629
T1  - Anxiety and depression in patients with polycystic ovarian syndrome
T3  - 22nd FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rio de Janeiro Brazil.
A1  - Tarar S.H. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objectives: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a disease of females of reproductive age and is present in at least 6.5% women. Its features include polycystic ovaries, oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea, increased androgens and are overweight. Psychological problems add up along with endocrine, metabolic and gynecological features, affecting quality of life and psychological well-being. Method(s): Cross-sectional study conducted from March 2017 to February 2018 after ethical approval. Non-probability consecutive sampling was used. 100 patients having PCOS were included in study after their consent. Clinical characteristics of PCOS were noted. Anxiety and depression were assessed using DSM-V criteria. Statistical analysis was done using SPSS 20.0. Result(s): Mean age was 25.13+6.32 years, mean weight 78.33+17.22 kg and mean BMI 29.88+6.76 Kg/m2. Symptoms included oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea (97%), hirsutism (76%), hair fall (67%), acne (66%), weight gain (55%), hypertension (27%), heaviness of voice (16%), enlargement of clitoris (15%), and hyperglycemia (6%). Presence of hirsutism, oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea, hypertension, weight gain, hair loss and acne were significantly associated with PCOS (p<0.05). BMI was independent risk factor for development of anxiety (p=0.001) and depression (p=0.000). Depression and anxiety significantly associated with PCOS (p<0.001). Conclusion(s): Anxiety and depression are significantly associated with PCOS.
