771. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 624606896
T1  - Aerobic physical training improves sexual function and qol of pcos women: Randomized conrrolled tria
T3  - 22nd FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rio de Janeiro Brazil.
A1  - Lara L.
A1  - Lopes I.P.
A1  - Dos Reis R.M.
A1  - Ribeiro V.B.
A1  - De Souza H.C.D.
A1  - Silva R.C. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objectives: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS) affects 5 to 10% of women. PCOS has been linked to sexual dysfunction, increased anxiety and depression, and reduced quality of life due to phenotypic changes such as increased weight and hip and waist circumferences in these women. Physical exercises might be relevant to improve these conditions. To date, there are few studies evaluating the effects of aerobic exercise training on sexual function and quality of life in PCOS women, and thus, this study aimed to evaluate the effect of aerobic physical training on sexual function in these women. Method(s): This was a randomized controlled clinical trial (registered as RBR-78QTWY) that included 69 PCOS women randomized to three groups: 23 women to continuous aerobic training (CAG), 22 volunteers to intermittent aerobic training (IAG), and 24 volunteers to the control group without training (CG). Testosterone plasma levels, as well as Female Sexual Function Index (FSFI), Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HAD), and Questionnaire Quality of Life -SF- 36 total scores were applied before and after 16-week of intervention. Result(s): After 16-weeks: waist hip ratio reduced in IAG; testosterone levels reduced and FSFI total score increased in CAG and IAG; score for satisfaction and pain domains increased in CAG; scores for desire, excitation, lubrication, and orgasm increased in IAG; scores for anxiety and depression reduced in CAG and IAG; CAG showed increased SF-36 scores regarding physical aspects, general health status vitality, social and emotional aspects, and mental health; IAG showed increased SF-36 scores regarding functional capacity, general health status, vitality, social aspects, emotional aspects, and mental health. Conclusion(s): Both aerobic physical training protocols were effective to improve sexual function and quality of life, and to reduce the risk for anxiety and depression in women with PCOS. Intermittent aerobic physical training was shown to be more effective in improving the greater number of FSFI domains compared to the continuous aerobic exercise protocol.
