AN  - 623112970
T1  - Mindfulness-based stress reduction decreases glucose and increases emotional quality of life in women with polycystic ovary syndrome
T3  - 100th Annual Meeting of the Endocrine Society, ENDO 2018. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - Raja-Khan N.
A1  - Agito K.
A1  - Shah J.
A1  - Stetter C.M.
A1  - Gustafson T.S.
A1  - Socolow H.
A1  - Kunselman A.R.
A1  - Reibel D.K.
A1  - Legro R.S. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Stress may contribute to increased diabetes and cardiovascular disease risk in women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). The objective was to investigate the effects of Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR) in the subgroup of PCOS women in a randomized controlled trial of MBSR in overweight or obese women. We randomized 32 women with PCOS and body mass index (BMI) >= 25 kg/m2 to 8 weeks of MBSR or health education control (HE). At baseline 8 weeks and 16 weeks fasting blood work and questionnaires were administered. Our overall hypothesis was that MBSR would increase mindfulness, reduce stress and ultimately lead to favorable changes in blood glucose, psychological distress and quality of life. Twenty PCOS women completed the study. Results were analyzed by intention-to-treat. The two groups were similar in BMI (mean +/- SD, MBSR 39.8 +/- 5.8 and HE 40.0 +/- 9.0 kg/m2). The MBSR group was older than the HE group so all analyses were adjusted for age (mean +/- SD, MBSR 40.0 +/- 10.2 and HE 30.5 +/- 6.3 years). Compared to HE, MBSR significantly increased the primary outcome mindfulness assessed with the CI) in MBSR was 5.1 (0.5 to 9.6) (28.5% change from baseline) vs. HE -1.6 (-6.2 to 3.0), P = 0.04]. Compared to HE, MBSR significantly increased emotional quality of life assessed with the PCOS Questionnaire (PCOSQ) at 8 weeks [MBSR 0.2 (-0.1 to 0.6) (4.7% change from baseline) vs. HE -0.3 (-0.7 to 0.0), P = 0.03]. Compared to HE, MBSR significantly reduced stress assessed with the Perceived Stress Scale-10 at 16 weeks [MBSR -4.3 (-6.1 to -2.6) (-18.6% change from baseline) vs. HE -0.5 (-2.5 to 1.5), P = 0.01]. In the MBSR group there were significant reductions in fasting glucose at 8 weeks [-12.6 (-24.6 to -0.6) mg/dl, P = 0.04)], Ferriman-Gallwey hirsutism score at 8 weeks [-1.9 (-3.7 to -0.1), P = 0.04)], and anxiety assessed with BSI-18 at 16 weeks [-3.9 (-7.7 to -0.2), P = 0.04)] compared to baseline. Fasting glucose, hirsutism and anxiety did not significantly improve in the HE group. The between-group differences did not reach statistical significance, possibly because this study was not powered to detect these differences. There were no significant changes in weight, BMI, blood pressure, testosterone, hemoglobin A1c, fasting insulin, HOMA-IR, lipid profile and hsCRP. In conclusion, in women with PCOS MBSR significantly reduces stress and increases emotional quality of life, and may have beneficial effects on glucose, hirsutism, and anxiety without changing body weight or insulin resistance. Potential mechanisms include physiological changes in the HPA axis and sympathetic nervous system. Future long-term clinical trials will be key for establishing MBSR as an effective tool in the management of PCOS.
