AN  - 622969935
T1  - In-patient sleep quality during nasal high flow therapy in chronic hypercapnic COPD patients
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Nilius G.
A1  - Domanski U.
A1  - Schrder M.
A1  - Tatkov S. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Rationale Overnight non-invasive respiratory support is essential in the treatment of patients with restrictive ventilation disturbances, improving quality of Life (QoL) and life expectancy. The use of nasal high flow (NHF) as a form of respiratory support in chronic hypercapnic respiratory failure may affect sleep. This study compares the sleep quality of inpatient chronic hypercapnic COPD patients during NHF or low flow oxygen therapy (LOT) as a control. Methods 35 stable hypercapnic COPD patients (21 female, Age: 67.6+/-6.9 years, BMI: 23.8+/-6.6 kg/m2, baseline pCO2: 55.8+/-6.0 mmHg, FEV1: 27.8+/-8.0% of predicted) were included in this randomized crossover study. Patients were invited to participate in the study of three attended polysomnography (PSG) recordings, specifically a baseline PSG with LOT and two randomized PSG with NHF rates of 20l/min and 35l/min. A short training course with NHF was preceded the treatment nights. Overnight Tissue CO2 (TcCO2) was measured during the attended PSG's (TOSCA, Radiometer). Results The arousal Index was 35.415.6% in baseline and dropped to 29.7+/-17.0% under NHF 20l/min (p=0.006) and 30.2+/-14.7% NHF 35L/min (p=0.064). Sleep efficiency values did not differ significantly (p=0.372 baseline vs NHF20, p=0.265 baseline vs NHF35). The AHI was 2.22.6 baseline and 5.1+/-9.3 NHF 20l/min and 4.6+/-5.26 NHF 35L/min. The results of the PSG parameters are presented in table 1. Conclusions In chronic hypercapnic patients NHF 20 and 35 l/min during night does not influence the sleep quality, induce central sleep apnea or arousals. (Table presented) .
