AN  - 622969549
T1  - Validation of a scalable efficient interoperable linkage process for patient-level emr data to patient-reported registration data within the COPD foundation patient powered research network: Building on common pcornet data networks toward a comprehensive COPD research data resource
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Mularski R.A.
A1  - Clark B.
A1  - Pasquale C.
A1  - Gillespie S.E.
A1  - Crawford P.
A1  - Malanga E.
A1  - Malanga V.
A1  - Yawn B.P.
A1  - McBurnie M.
A1  - Davis K.J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - RATIONALE: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) affects 12-29 million individuals in the U.S. and is the 3rd leading cause of death. We developed and tested a mechanism for the COPD Patient Powered Research Network (PPRN), as one of the research entities in PCORnet, to link comprehensive electronic medical record (EMR) data from consented participants to patient-reported outcomes (PRO) measurements collected longitudinally in the Network. METHOD(S): The COPD PPRN has been engaged in a nation-wide endeavor to enroll patients with COPD into a patient-led registry for multi-mode survey research, electronic data capture, and multi-site and longitudinal study conduct. Using a technology platform that is flexible and scalable, we tested data linkage from a sub-database containing up to ten years of comprehensive EMR common-data model transformed data for the subset of COPD PPRN participants who are also Kaiser Northwest CONCERT/PORTAL study members. Data were accessed via a RESTful API and managed by the Corepoint Integration Engine to authenticate communication and securely transfer data to DatStat EMR table shells at COPD PPRN. Validation analyses assessed the concordance and completeness against the original PORTAL data node and a research-proven CONCERT Data Hub for these overlapping patients. RESULT(S): Overall the COPD PPRN has enrolled over 6,400 participants; 360 were identified as being overlapping participants with available EMR data and 346 (96.1%) met completeness of demographic data and satisfied the 50% threshold as PRO survey completers. In general, transferred data values and derived variables were nearly perfectly concordant between data sources (all 96,936 records aligned; of 136,822 associated diagnoses, 420 extra (0.002%) and of 150,420 procedures, 163 extra (0.001%) were identified due to a 10 month difference in data locks of source data. Two data error sources were identified and rectified: 3 duplicate (<0.01%) records were generated due to competing server demands during data upload resulting in intermittent server timeouts and a human coding error (later corrected) resulted in discordant values relating to a single variable, death source. CONCLUSION(S): We have validated linkage mechanisms and API transfer methodology that offers future scalability and interoperability across collaborating PCORnet entities to facilitate enhanced database and facilitated prospective research. The COPD PPRN has established a large registry of COPD patients across the disease spectrum including significant multimorbidity that has now linked self-reported longitudinal quality-of-life and PRO data with comprehensive EMR data in an efficient platform within the PCORnet enterprise to conduct patient partnered research.
