783. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622478554
T1  - Exploring how knowledge, attitudes, and practices affect health-related quality of life in women diagnosed with polycystic ovarian syndrome
T3  - 2018 Annual Meeting of the American Pharmacists Association, APHA 2018. Nashville, TN United States.
A1  - Nguyen T. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objective: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine condition that affects more than 10% of women at reproductive age in the United States and can be difficult to manage. Management of the condition involves both nonpharmacological and pharmacological treatments, however, few clear guidelines are available to assist health-care providers in diagnosing and managing PCOS. Currently, few studies in the United States have been done to evaluate the different factors that can contribute to the health-related quality of life of women diagnosed with PCOS. The primary objective of this study is to determine how knowledge, attitudes and practices affect health-related quality of life (HRQoL) in women diagnosed with Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS). Method(s): This study used a cross-sectional online survey administered using Qualtrics. Women over 18 years old, residing in the United States, English-speaking, and had been diagnosed with PCOS were recruited from the Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome Awareness Association Facebook website. The survey contained six main sections including questions regarding quality of PCOS information received, current and/ or previous pharmacological and non-pharmacological treatment, pharmacological adherence and discontinuation, PCOS health-related quality of life, perceptions towards a PCOS management clinic and demographics. A standardized PCOS HRQoL questionnaire was used. Data was entered and analyzed using SPSS 22.0. Descriptive statistics and bivariate analysis were used to determine associations between dependent and independent variables. The p-value was set at p < 0.05. Result(s): The mean age of participants was 30.8 (SD=+/-5.73) years old and most women had been diagnosed for greater than 2 years (79.1%, n=480/607). Most women (520/606, 85.8%) had at least some college education or higher. Most women (78.4%; n=476/607) indicated they had previously or were currently utilizing pharmacological therapies for management of PCOS symptoms. Previous or current use of pharmacological treatment did not significantly affect HRQoL scores (p > 0.05). Over 80% of women (86.2%; n = 523/607) reported excellent PCOS knowledge. Women with excellent knowledge had higher HRQoL menstrual problems scores compared to women with less than excellent knowledge (p=0.03). Most women stated that they had not received the right amount of information on various topics, including prescription medications, when they were diagnosed with PCOS. Women who had received adequate information for each of the topics had higher overall HRQoL scores (p=0.001). Conclusion(s): Improved knowledge and attitudes affects health-related quality of life in patients diagnosed with PCOS. However, most women felt that they were not receiving the right amount of information regarding overall management of PCOS when they were diagnosed. It will be important to focus on what kind of information health care providers are providing to their patients regarding PCOS and howthis can be improved to enhance PCOS management practices. Future studies need to determine the role pharmacists can play to improve knowledge, attitudes and behaviors in women diagnosed with PCOS to advance overall management.
