784. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622478544
T1  - Exploring the role of medication adherence on health-related quality of life in women diagnosed with polycystic ovarian syndrome
T3  - 2018 Annual Meeting of the American Pharmacists Association, APHA 2018. Nashville, TN United States.
A1  - Nguyen T. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objective: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine condition that affects more than 10% of women at reproductive age in the United States and can be difficult to manage. Management of the condition involves both nonpharmacological and pharmacological treatments, however, few clear guidelines are available to assist health-care providers in diagnosing and managing PCOS. Currently, research has not been done to evaluate how medication adherence can affect the health-related quality of life of women diagnosed with PCOS. The primary objective is to determine if adherence to pharmacological therapy affects health related quality of life (HRQoL) in women diagnosed with polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) and to determine the role of health care professionals to improve PCOS pharmacological management. Method(s): This study used a cross-sectional online survey administered using Qualtrics. Women over 18 years old, residing in the United States, English-speaking, and had been diagnosed with PCOS were recruited from the Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome Awareness Association Facebook website. The survey contained six main sections including questions regarding quality of PCOS information received, current and/ or previous pharmacological and non-pharmacological treatment, pharmacological adherence and discontinuation, PCOS health-related quality of life (HRQoL), perceptions towards a PCOS management clinic and demographics. A standardized PCOS HRQoL questionnaire was used. Self-reported medication adherence was assessed with the validated question, "Thinking about the past 4 weeks, please rate your ability to take your medication as prescribed." The response was provided on a 5-point Likert scale, where 1 was "poor" and 5 was "excellent." Women who indicated "excellent" ability, where classified as being adherent. Data was entered and analyzed using SPSS 22.0. Descriptive statistics and bivariate analysis were used to determine associations between dependent and independent variables. The p-value was set at P < 0.05. Result(s): The mean age of participants was 30.8 (SD=+/-5.73) years old. Most women (78.4%; n=476/607) indicated they had previously or were currently utilizing pharmacological therapies for management of PCOS symptoms. The top three currently used medications were metformin, hormonal contraceptives and anti-androgens with 43.3%, 61.1% and 49.1% of women indicating "excellent" adherence, respectively. Women who were adherent had better overall HRQoL scores compared to non-adherent women (median (IQR)= 2.71 (2.12-3.42) vs. 2.42 (1.79-3.10) p=0.002). Compared to nonadherent women, women who were adherent also had better HRQoL Emotions (median (IQR)= 2.87 (2.12-3.87), vs. 2.62 (1.87-3.31) p=0.005), Infertility (median (IQR)= 2.75 (1.25-5.00) vs. 2.00 (1.25-3.25) p=0.001) and Menstrual Problems scores (median (IQR)= 3.00 (2.00-4.00) vs. 2.50 (1.50-3.75) p=0.029). Most women (91.6%; n=556/607) stated they would benefit from a PCOS management clinic and 54.2% (n = 329/ 607) indicated they would be willing to seek information about PCOS prescription medications from pharmacists. Conclusion(s): Women with excellent adherence to PCOS pharmacological treatments have higher HRQoL scores. Excellent adherence, however, was not reported in most women who were taking at least one of the top three currently used medications. Because more than half of the women indicated they would be willing to seek information from pharmacists about PCOS prescription medications, pharmacists have a vital role in improving adherence rates and in turn health related quality of life. Future research should focus on developing evidencebased interventions to improve adherence to pharmacological treatments in women diagnosed with PCOS.
