786. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622331665
T1  - Which outcome domains are important in palliative care and when? Results of an international expert workshop
T3  - 10th World Research Congress of the European Association for Palliative Care, EAPC 2018. Bern Switzerland.
A1  - De Wolf-Linder S.
A1  - Dawkins M.
A1  - Wicks F.
A1  - Pask S.
A1  - Eagar K.
A1  - Evans C.J.
A1  - Higginson I.J.
A1  - Murtagh F.E.M. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Background: Patient-level outcomes in palliative care (PC) are hard to capture, as patients receiving PC are steadily declining in health. It is important to identify which outcome domains are most important, to focus efforts to capture outcomes, improve quality of care, and minimize the burden of outcome collection. Aim(s): To recommend domains of PC most important for outcome-based quality indicators (QI), and the optimal time period (unit of measurement) over which these outcomes should be measured. Method(s): The abbreviated MORECare Transparent Expert Consultation, adopting a Nominal Group Technique, was used for this workshop. Experts were identified through the Outcome Assessment and Complexity Collaborative (OACC) and Palliative Care Outcome Collaborative (PCOC) networks, through authors of the EAPC White Paper on Outcome Measurement, and through screening of oral presentation titles for outcomes work at the 2016 EAPC conference, at which this workshop was conducted. Following a pre-workshop briefing and the structured facilitated Nominal Groups, participants ranked their top three priorities on outcome based QIs and unit of measurements. Data were analysed descriptively after weighting by rank. Rationales from participants were analysed thematically using an inductive approach. Result(s): 33 clinicians and researchers working in PC outcome measurement globally participated. Two groups (n=16 and n=17) answered one question each (QIs or unit of measures) covering the right domains in PC. Participants' years of experience in PC ranged from 10.9 to 14.7, and experience in outcome measures ranged 5.8 to 6.4 years. Top ranked domains were 'Overall Wellbeing/Quality of life' (mean score 2.75), 'Pain' (mean score 2.06), and 'Information needs and preferences' (mean score 2.06). 'Phase of Illness' was recommended as the preferred unit of measurement, as it reflects how acute PC needs are, and is already used internationally. Conclusion(s): The domains of "overall wellbeing/quality of life", "pain", and "information needs and preferences" are recommended for regular measurement by palliative care clinicians and researchers, with 'Phase of Illness' proposed as the most useful unit of measurement. International adoption of these recommendations will help standardize approaches to improving the quality of palliative care.
