789. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 620079157
T1  - Pulmonary arterial hypertension: An enemy in disguise?
T3  - 47th Society of Critical Care Medicine Critical Care Congress, SCCM 2018. San Antonio, TX United States.
A1  - Oporto B.
A1  - Lai L.
A1  - Gulati S.
A1  - Pillai A.
A1  - Hameed A.A. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Learning Objectives: Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) associated with congenital heart disease (CHD) is a rare disease. CHDPAH is a challenging diagnosis due to the nonspecific nature of its symptomatology and is often obscured or confounded by coexisting medical conditions. Here we have a case-report about a patient who presented multiple times to the emergency department complaining of relentless dyspnea due to presumed failed outpatient treatment of COPD when the patient actually had pulmonary arterial hypertension-congenital heart disease. Method(s): 48-year-old male with a PMH of multiple comorbidities and hospitalizations for dyspnea in the past, presented to the ED complaining of progressively worsening exertional dyspnea. He was found afebrile, hypoxic, BP 148/99 mmHg, RR of 22 rpm, HR 96 bpm. Physical exam revealed a loud diastolic murmur in the pulmonic area. Labs: Hto 58.6 %. UDS positive cocaine. ABG: pH7.27/PaO2/ pCO2 91.6/HCO3 42.2. Chest CT: enlargement of main pulmonary artery. Echocardiogram: EF of 65%, severely enlarged right ventricular cavity, septal flattening of the intra-ventricular septum, moderately dilated right atrial cavity, a positive bubble study. Patient was admitted to the ICU, intubated, mechanically ventilated, received IV steroids, furosemide and nebulization. A right heart catheterization revealed: right atrial pressure 29, right ventricular pressure 70/39, pulmonary arterial pressure 70/23. During his hospitalization his oxygen requirements remained high, but improved after sildenafil. Finally, he was transferred to a tertiary center with a pulmonary hypertension center. Result(s): Pulmonary arterial hypertension is a fatal and rare disease with a poor prognosis and quality of life despite current medical treatments. Presently more than 90% of children diagnosed with CHD survive into adulthood and only 5-10% will develop pulmonary arterial hypertension. Its diagnosis is often obscured or confounded by coexisting medical conditions such as obstructive sleep apnea (OSA), chronic obstructive lung disease (COPD) or deconditioning. Unfortunately most patients with pulmonary hypertension are diagnosed late at an advanced stage. Not only because of the non-specificity of its symptoms but also because of low physician awareness in relatively rare diseases. The physician must have a high index of suspicion to diagnose this disease since timely intervention can improve quality of life.
