840. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 625788471
T1  - Outpatient initiation of long term domiciliary non-invasive ventilation in chronic stable type II respiratory failure
T3  - European Respiratory Society International Congress, ERS 2017. Milan Italy.
A1  - Glover R.
A1  - Lloyd J.
A1  - Ismail I. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Introduction: We have recently begun initiating NIV in a single outpatient session for individuals with chronic stable type II respiratory failure; initial follow up is guided by remote monitoring. We hope to circumnavigate the resource intense standard approach of elective admission. Aim(s): The aim of this study is to retrospectively review the efficacy of ventilation when long term NIV is commenced using this method. Method(s): Subjects baseline, postitration and first follow up blood gases will be compared to identify the efficacy of ventilation; compliance data obtained via remote monitoring over a fixed period will be used to assess patient acceptance. Result(s): Preliminary data is displayed, data collection is ongoing. Table 1. Blood gases at baseline and following NIV 11 clinically stable patients underwent O/P set up between February and October, 2016. No adverse events were recorded. PCO2 was significantly reduced from baseline in comparison to the post titration (p=0.0313) and first review blood gas (p=0.0044); PO2 significantly improved at the first review (p=0.0424). Usage was reported at 5.4hr (SD2.8), 4.9hr (SD2.9) and 6.3 (SD2.1) at the first 7 days, first 28 days and last 28 days, respectively. Conclusion(s): Preliminary results show that blood gas improvement is significant and usage of NIV is acceptable in this patient cohort. Further data analysis will focus on nocturnal oxygenation and change in quality of life.
