842. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623188299
T1  - Health-related quality of life (HRQL) in women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)
T3  - 11th Congress of the European Menopause and Andropause Society, EMAS 2017. Amsterdam Netherlands.
A1  - Yoldemir T.
A1  - Angin P.
A1  - Ramoglu S.
A1  - Atasayan K. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Aim: The aim is to identify the health-related quality of life (HRQL) in women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) by using short-form health survey (SF-36) and PCOS Questionnaire (PCOSQ). Material(s) and Method(s): One hundred eleven (49 ofwhominfertile and 62 fertile PCOS) women younger than 35 years of age and 47 age matched infertile non-PCOS women who applied to Infertility and Gynecology Clinics at Marmara University affiliated Pendik Education and Research Hospital, Istanbul were included in this prospective survey. HRQL was assessed with the Turkish version of the 36-item short-form health survey (SF-36). Polycystic Ovary Syndrome Questionnaire (PCOSQ) was also filled for each patient. Result(s): Both SF-36 and PCOSQ score were lowest in infertile PCOS women. PCOSQ scores were significantly lower in fertile PCOS group than infertile non-PCOS group. Mental health and vitality domain scores of SF-36 were the lowest among infertile non-PCOS women. General health and vitality domain scores were the lowest among infertile PCOS and fertile PCOS women. Menstrual problems were the worst parameter affecting the QoL in each group. Conclusion(s): In each of the three groups, there were weakmoderate correlations between each domain in the SF-36 and PCOSQ. We have shown that PCOSQ could be an optional evaluation tool aside from SF-36 in determining QoL among young PCOS women seeking conception. Since our survey medical center which gave medical care service to women from middle and low socioeconomic classes, our results should be confirmed by a large multicenter survey enrolling women from all different socioeconomic classes.
