AN  - 622461969
T1  - Prostate cancer outcomes Norway (PCO-Norway): A national, prospective collection of patient reported outcome measures (PROMs)
T3  - 9th European Multidisciplinary Meeting on Urological Cancers, EMUC 2017. Barcelona Spain.
A1  - Gjelsvik Y.M.
A1  - Fossa S.D.
A1  - Haug E.S.
A1  - Kvale R.
A1  - Myklebust T.
A1  - Iversen M.M.
A1  - Nygard J.F.
A1  - Brenden K.H.
A1  - Ursin G.
A1  - Johannesen T.B. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Introduction & Objectives: Although prostate cancer (PCa) is a common cancer diagnosis in older men, the 5-year overall relative survival is very high (93%). It is therefore important to understand how the disease and treatment affect patients' general well-being and activities of daily life. Such analyses must take into consideration both the patient's age, disease stage at time of diagnosis and type of treatment. To aid treatment decisions considering both prognosis and quality of life (QoL), more un-biased, preferably population-based knowledge is needed about treatment-related adverse effects and QoL among PCa patients. To achieve this, we are conducting a national, prospective collection of patient reported outcome measures (PROMs) for PCa patients. Material(s) and Method(s): All Norwegian men diagnosed with PCa in 2017-2019, regardless of age and cancer stage, are identified by the Cancer Registry of Norway (CRN) as soon as possible after diagnosis. Controls without any history of PCa are identified from the National Registry and frequency matched on age and geographic region. Potential participants are invited by digital or regular mail to a survey on men's health. The participants complete the baseline questionnaire before treatment, and the follow-up questionnaires after 1 and 3 years. The questionnaire consists of EQ-5D-DL on general health, EORTC-QLQ-C30 (cancer specific) and EPIC-26 (PCa-specific). Those participating electronically safely log on with a bank issued electronic identity card frequently used by many Norwegians for both public and private digital services. Respondents can also participate using the paper questionnaire. The paper questionnaire and a pre-paid return envelope is included in the invitations sent via regular mail. At the CRN, paper questionnaires are scanned and converted using optical character recognition. The questionnaire data are linked with data in the Norwegian Prostate Cancer Registry at the CRN, and eventually other public registries. Hospitals with the necessary ethical approval can receive individual questionnaire data, for quality assurance, feedback and/or individual patient follow-up. Result(s): The system for inviting newly diagnosed PCa patients to the survey and receiving questionnaires functions as planned, and will be used nationally for other cancer types in the future. 39% of the men invited so far have had an official digital mailbox, resulting in substantial cost savings compared to sending all questionnaires by regular mail. The initial response rate is around 50% after 12 weeks of PROMs collection. Around 50% of the participants respond electronically. We have started to transfer individual questionnaire data to the patients' hospitals. Conclusion(s): The infrastructure for sending out and receiving PROMs questionnaires to newly diagnosed PCa patients is feasible on a nationwide level. Initial response rates are viewed as satisfactory.
