T1  - The influence of quality of life on cancer treatment satisfaction and care
T3  - 24th Annual Conference of the International Society for Quality of Life Research, ISOQOL 2017. Philadelphia, PA United States.
A1  - Wenzel L.
A1  - Mukamel D.B.
A1  - Osann K.
A1  - Havrilesky L.
A1  - Wright A.
A1  - Walker J.
A1  - Alvarez R.
A1  - Van Le L.
A1  - Robison K.
A1  - Randall L.
A1  - Wakabayashi M.
A1  - Sparks L.
A1  - Hsieh S.
A1  - Wahi A.
A1  - Ladd H.
A1  - Lipscomb J.
A1  - Cohn D. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Aims: We conducted a randomized clinical trial to test a novel Patient Centered Outcome Aid (PCOA). This aid was designed to facilitate shared decision-making and help ovarian cancer patients assimilate information and identify quality of life (QOL), toxicity and survival trade-offs between treatment options, based on their preferences and personal clinical characteristics. In this study we identify the outcomes that were significantly influenced by QOL. Method(s): In this multi-site US sample of newly diagnosed ovarian cancer patients, assessments were obtained prior to randomization, during active treatment, and 9 months post enrollment. Outcomes included satisfaction with the treatment decision and care, and decisional regret. Comparisons were made using t-tests and multivariate methods, adjusting for patient covariates. Multivariate linear models were used to investigate predictors of the outcomes. QOL and shared decisionmaking were independent variables in the models. Result(s): 124 patients were randomized (PCOA N = 64; UC N = 60). There were no differences between study arms on primary or secondary outcomes. However, low QOL and low shared decision-making, and their interaction, were significant predictors of low satisfaction with the treatment decision at treatment initiation (multiple r = 0.76), six months (multiple r = 0.48) and nine months (r = 0.58). They were also significant predictors of decisional regret (multiple r = 0.48 and 0.36 at 6 and 9 months). Further, satisfaction with the decision was significantly lower for those with low QOL (p = .002) throughout the study, with the most recent QOL being the best predictor of low satisfaction (p<0.001), and lower satisfaction with care. At study entry, those with low QOL also reported less shared decision-making during the treatment decision process, and among PCOA participants, those with low QOL were significantly more concerned about developing future treatment toxicities (OR = 1.06 p<.05). Patient covariates including age, stage, treatment and neoadjuvant status were not associated with differences in outcomes. Conclusion(s): QOL evaluation is a useful tool to predict and assess satisfaction with the cancer treatment decision over time, as well as satisfaction with care. QOL evaluations can be valuable in cancer treatment planning, particularly since those with low QOL perceive themselves as less engaged in the decision process.
