866. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617709143
T1  - Acute respiratory failure in a patient with ipf following nebulized and intravenous stem cell therapy
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Raynor J.
A1  - Cervellione K.L.
A1  - Desai P.
A1  - Thurm C. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Given the limited treatment options and generally poor prognosis of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF), patients and their families are drawn to experimental medications and off-label treatments to help prolong and improve quality of life. Stem cell therapy is a newly emerging option that is available through a limited number of centers. Given the limited published cases of treatment with stem cell therapy in patients with IPF, little is known about the potential adverse events. We present a case of a patient with IPF who developed acute respiratory failure shortly after undergoing intravenous and nebulized stem cell replacement therapy. A 72-year-old male patient with a history of IPF presented with worsening dyspnea over several weeks. Patient reported no new medications, fever, chills, sputum production, or chest pain and no previous hospitalizations. The family reported that he had received intravenous and nebulized autologous stem cell therapy through an experimental program 4 weeks prior to and again 2 weeks prior to current admission. On presentation, the patient's oxygen saturation was 68% on 2L nasal cannula; saturation improved to 85% on non-rebreather face mask. He was tachycardic, tachypneic, normotensive and afebrile. He appeared malnourished and fatigued. Physical exam revealed bilateral lower lobe rales without wheeze or evidence of consolidation. Labs were significant for WBC=17.6, glucose=299, BUN=32, creatinine=1.2, bicarb=18, and lactic acid=6.5. Rapid influenza, urine legionella antigen, urine streptococcal pneumonia antigen and blood cultures were negative. ABG on bipap (10/5) with an Fio2 of 50% revealed pH=7.33, PCO2=31, PO2=65, and HCO3=16.3. Patient was started on IV methylprednisolone and antibiotics. High resolution CT scan showed extensive ground glass attenuation in a "crazy paving" pattern in a perihilar distribution superimposed on extensive interstitial lung disease, consistent with acute exacerbation of underlying IPF. Lactate improved over several hours. Over 12 hours his oxygenation significantly improved and WBC normalized. He remained on bipap for 3 days and IV methylprednisone for 5 days, at which time oral prednisone was started and tapered over the next month. He was discharged to inpatient rehab on day 6 and subsequently returned home on supplemental oxygen. Stem cell replacement was felt to be the most likely trigger of exacerbation. Infection was a less-likely culprit in this situation. It will be important for clinicians to recognize some of the possible side effects of stem cell replacement given its increasing prevalence in the experimental arena. In our patient, there was rapid improvement to therapy, including prednisone.
