AN  - 617709073
T1  - Longitudinal follow-up data from enrollees in the COPD foundation patient-powered research network: methods and outcomes
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Mannino D.M.
A1  - Choate R.
A1  - Walsh J.
A1  - Mularski R.A.
A1  - Pasquale C.
A1  - Clark W.
A1  - Malanga E.
A1  - Gillespie S.
A1  - McBurnie M.
A1  - Crawford P. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - RATIONALE: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) affects 12-29 million individuals in the US. Deficits in provision of care for COPD patients indicate that patient-centered outcomes research in COPD is needed. Working under contract from Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI), we developed the COPD Foundation Patient Powered Research Network (PPRN) as one of the research entities in PCORnet: a national Patient-Centered Outcome Research Network and have begun collection of longitudinal data on our cohort. METHOD(S): The COPD Foundation PPRN has been engaged in a nation-wide endeavor to enroll patients with COPD and those at risk into a patient-led registry for multi-mode survey research, electronic data capture, patient-reported outcomes (PRO) measurement and multi-site and longitudinal study conduct. Using a technology platform that is flexible and scalable, we have launched longitudinal data collection in July 2016. Data was collected from eligible individuals who completed the baseline survey online using the COPD PPRN's technology platform. Eligible patients are sent an initial invitation to complete the longitudinal survey and receive automated reminder emails if no response on 2nd, 7th day and 30th day, 3 months, 6 months and 1 year. Longitudinal PRO's collection includes general and disease specific domains gathering information on diagnosis, comorbidity, respiratory specific items, exacerbation history, smoking history, oxygen use, and core quality of life and symptom PROs. RESULT(S): Overall, 5,440 participants are consented into the registry; as of October 2016, 869 were eligible to complete the follow-up survey and 225 (25.9%) have completed the longitudinal survey to date. Among all the eligible participants older (OR=1.02, p=0.03) respondents, males (OR=1.47, p=0.02) and current non-smokers (OR=3.03, p=0.001) had significantly greater odds of completing the longitudinal survey. Patients with asthma, those who reported using oxygen, or reported being hospitalized prior to baseline were not significantly different between the two groups (responders and non-responders). Among 225 participants who completed the longitudinal survey, CAT score at follow-up had a mean decrease of 0.56 (SD 4.95) compared to baseline, average fatigue score had an increase of 0.02 (SD 0.82) compared to baseline. The proportion of current smokers has decreased from 5.79% at baseline to 3.57% at follow up. CONCLUSION(S): The COPD Foundation PPRN has provided an efficient means of evaluating patients with COPD both cross-sectionally and longitudinally. Some patient demographic characteristics (older age, male, current nonsmokers) associated with better participation in the longitudinal survey. (Table Presented).
