868. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617709053
T1  - Linking patient-level emr data to patient-reported registration data within the copd foundation patient powered research network: Pilot work toward a scalable efficient interoperable comprehensive research data resource
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Mularski R.A.
A1  - Walsh J.
A1  - Clark W.
A1  - Pasquale C.
A1  - Gillespie S.
A1  - Crawford P.
A1  - Malanga E.
A1  - Malanga V.
A1  - Mannino D.M.
A1  - McBurnie M. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - RATIONALE: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) affects 12-29 million individuals in the US and is the 3rd leading cause of death. Working under contract from Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) and led by the COPD Foundation, we developed the COPD Patient Powered Research Network (PPRN) as one of the research entities in PCORnet and subsequently piloted linkage of comprehensive electronic medical record (EMR) data to patient-reported outcomes (PRO) measurements. METHOD(S): The COPD PPRN has been engaged in a nation-wide endeavor to enroll patients with COPD into a patient-led registry for multi-mode survey research, electronic data capture, and multi-site and longitudinal study conduct. Using a technology platform that is flexible and scalable, we piloted data linkage as authorized by COPD PPRN patient consent from a sub-database containing up to ten years of comprehensive EMR common-data model transformed/formatted data for the subset of COPD PPRN participants who are also Kaiser Northwest CONCERT/PORTAL study members. Data was accessed via a RESTful API and was managed by the Corepoint Integration Engine to authenticate communication and securely transfer data to DatStat EMR table shells at COPD PPRN. Current analyses summarize characterizing linked data for merged PRO/EMR COPD PPRN participants. RESULT(S): Overall the COPD PPRN has enrolled 5,540 participants; 360 were identified as being Kaiser Northwest participants who have available EMR data extracted in the CONCERT/PORTAL databases and 346 were included (96.1%) as provided demographic data and satisfied the 50% threshold as PRO survey completers. Participants had a mean (+SD) age of 72.1 +/- 8.6 years; 53% were female; 26% reported an acute exacerbation leading to emergency department visit and 19% an exacerbation with hospitalization in the last year; 11% currently smoke. The mean SF-1 score was 3.4 (SD 0.86); mean dyspnea score (MMRC on 0-4 range) was 1.8 (SD 1.1); the mean CAT score 18.4 (SD 7.2). Of those with spirometry in the EMR (66%), 94% had phenotype with airflow obstruction; 23% mild severity, 51% moderate, 22% severe. CONCLUSION(S): We have amassed a large registry of COPD patients across the disease spectrum with significant morbidity who have provided a range of self-reported quality-of-life and PRO data that now have been successfully linked to comprehensive EMR data. This pilot work with subsequent validation efforts can be a step towards creating an efficient scalable system for linking patient data across sources in the PCORnet enterprise to enhance PPRN PRO and registrant data for research.
