869. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617707122
T1  - Multidisciplinary approach to non-invasive ventilation in severe COPD patients: A pilot study
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Cheung D.
A1  - Theunisse C.
A1  - De Graaf N.
A1  - Scholten-Bakker M.
A1  - Willemsen S.
A1  - Ponssen H. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Rationale: Solid evidence for the effectiveness of non-invasive home ventilation in patients with severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is lacking due to conflicting study results. Recent work suggests that non-invasive home ventilation is more effective when high ventilator settings are used (>18 cm H2O). However, high ventilator settings are less comfortable for patients which might reduce patient adherence to non-invasive ventilation. We have developed a multidisciplinary approach to non-invasive ventilation aimed at optimizing patient acceptance and adherence. Low pressures are used in order to ventilate patients as comfortable as possible. We used this approach in severe COPD patients and compared in-hospital days and quality of life before versus 1 year after starting non-invasive home ventilation. Method(s): We included 57 GOLD stage IV COPD patients with a high disease burden. Patients were given instructions on the usage of Bi-level airway pressure (Bipap) by a ventilation practitioner during a one-day hospital stay. End positive airway pressure was 5 cm H2O, inspiratory pressure was < 14 cm H2O. Patients were treated for one year in combination with home visits by specialized respiratory nurses and a 24 hour calling service. Outcome measures included capillary PCO2, in-hospital days, Medical Research Council dyspnea (MRC) score, Clinical COPD Questionnaire (CCQ) score and Hospital Anxiety Depression Scale (HADS) score. Result(s): After 1 year 32 patients could be evaluated. Hospital days decreased by 10.0 (95 confidence interval (CI): 16.5 to 5.4, p=0.0021) from 18.0 +/- 21.1 [+/- SD] to 8.0 +/- 12.7 days. Capillary PCO2 decreased by 0.3 (CI: 0.6 to 0.1, p = 0.007) from 6.8 +/- 1.5 to 6.5 +/- 1.2. The MRC dyspnea score decreased by 0.7 (CI: -1.1 to -0.2, p=0.009) from 4.2 +/- 0.9 to 3.5 +/- 1.0. The CCQ score decreased by 0.7 (CI: 1.0 to 0.2, p = 0.006) from 3.4 +/- 1.1 to 2.7 +/- 1.1. The HADS anxiety score decreased by 1.6 (CI: 2.9 to 0.6, p = 0.003) from 7.2 +/- 3.7 to 5.6 +/- 4.2. The HADS depression score decreased by 1.6 (CI: 3.0 to 0.2, p = 0.027) from 8.3 +/- 3.6 to 6.7 +/- 4.7. Conclusion(s): This multidisciplinary approach to non-invasive ventilation in severe COPD patients with a high disease burden may lead to less in-hospital days and a better quality of life. Our findings underscore the need for a prospective randomized controlled trial examining the effects of this multidisciplinary approach to non-invasive ventilation.
