870. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617705379
T1  - MECP2 duplication syndrome: A rare cause of immune dysfunction and recurrent lower respiratory tract infections
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Hamberger E.
A1  - Buu M. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Introduction Recurrent lower respiratory infections are a common reason for pediatric pulmonary consultation. Further investigation is required if treatment of the presumed diagnosis does not result in stabilization of the patients clinical course. MECP2 duplication syndrome is a rare X-linked neurodevelopmental disorder known to cause seizures, hypotonia, motor delays, and recurrent infections. Chronic lower respiratory infections account for the greatest mortality in affected males. More than 80% require a tracheostomy by age 15 and patients often do not live through the second decade of life. We report a case of MECP2 duplication syndrome in a 7-year-old boy who was treated for severe persistent asthma until he presented with hypoxic and hypercapnic respiratory failure. Case A 7-year-old boy with a history of multiple asthma exacerbations, chronic cough, multiple pneumonias, and global developmental delay of unknown etiology presented with one day of wheezing and increased work of breathing that worsened precipitously despite albuterol, ipratropium, and oral steroids prescribed by his pediatrician. Initial evaluation showed hypoxemia, left upper lobe and lingular opacities, and severe respiratory acidosis (pH 7.06, pCO2 92). He had a prolonged hospitalization for mechanical ventilation, diagnostic bronchoscopy, and IV antibiotic treatment for pneumonia. He was evaluated for recurrent pneumonia and found to have aspiration of thin liquids by modified barium swallow and immune dysfunction with elevated IgG but poor immunologic memory. Array comparative genomic hybridization showed duplication of Xq28 which includes a duplication of the MECP2 gene. Specific genetic testing confirmed this diagnosis. At age 11, he continues to maintain good health and quality of life with multi-disciplinary management including gastrostomy tube for hydration, immunoglobulin replacement, aggressive airway clearance therapy and antibiotic therapy for respiratory infections, strict control of persistent asthma and physical therapy to maintain ambulation. Discussion This case report identifies a rare disorder associated with neurologic impairment, aspiration, hypotonia, and immune dysfunction involving the toll-like receptor signaling pathway. These risk factors result in recurrent lower respiratory infections and lead to an unfavorable prognosis with chronic respiratory failure. However, this patient continues to do well despite these co-morbidities and has not required a tracheostomy. Our case highlights the importance of a noninvasive multi-system approach in similar patients.
