880. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617436770
T1  - Long-term psychological and quality-of-life effects of active surveillance and watchful waiting after diagnosis of low-risk localised prostate cancer
T3  - Annual Scientific Meeting of the Australian and New Zealand Urogenital and Prostate, ANZUP 2017. Melbourne, VIC Australia.
A1  - Calopedos R.
A1  - Egger S.
A1  - O'Connell D.
A1  - Chambers S.
A1  - Woo H.H.
A1  - Smith D. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Background: Long-term psychological wellbeing and quality-of-life are important considerations when deciding whether to undergo active treatment for low-risk localised prostate cancer. Our aim was to assess the long-term effects of active surveillance (AS) and/or watchful waiting (WW) on psychological and quality-of-life outcomes for low-risk localised prostate cancer patients. Method(s): The Prostate Cancer Care and Outcome Study (PCOS) is a population-based prospective cohort study in New South Wales, Australia. Participants for these analyses were low-risk prostate cancer patients aged less than 70 years at diagnosis and who participated in the 10-year follow-up. Validated instruments assessed health-related quality-of-life and psychological outcomes relevant to prostate cancer patients. Adjusted mean differences (AMDs) in outcome scores between prostate cancer treatment groups were estimated using linear regression. Result(s): Compared to patients who received an active treatment, those who remained on AS/WW had greater fear of cancer recurrence (AMD = 10.6; 95%CI [1.5, 19.6]), distress (AMD = 6.0; 95%CI [0.9, 11.0]), hyperarousal (AMD = 5.3; 95%CI [0.5, 10.0]) and cognitive avoidance (AMD = 7.7; 95%CI [1.3, 14.1]); but they also had better urinary incontinence scores (AMD = -11.8; 95%CI [-21.9, -1.7]), better sexual summary scores (AMD = -19.1; 95%CI [-32.1, -6.1]) and less sexual bother (AMD = -24.2; 95%CI [-44.3, -4.1]). Limitations in this study include participant attrition and inability to assess baseline psychological measures. Conclusion(s): The avoidance of active treatment for low-risk prostate cancer provides long-term benefits in terms of certain physical aspects of quality of life, including long-term sexual health and reduced urinary leakage. These benefits, however, may come at a psychological cost, with long-term psychological outcomes such as distress and fear of cancer recurrence being significantly increased in the monitoring group. Our results suggest that Management of urinary obstructive and irritative symptoms, behavioural interventions and elucidation of the relatively low risks of cancer progression may help improve the psychological wellbeing of AS and WW patients.
