T3  - 31st Annual Clinical Research Meeting, Engaging the Stars of NASPAG, NASPAG 2017. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - Malcolm S.
A1  - Tuchman L.
A1  - Cheng Y.I.
A1  - Wang J.
A1  - Gomez-Lobo V. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Purpose: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrine disorder of adolescents and women. PCOS is associated with adverse outcomes including infertility, diabetes, metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular events and endometrial carcinoma. While evidence has shown that PCOS negatively impacts health related quality of life, adolescents also are concerned about their reproductive potential. Little is known about reproductive health behaviors, including patterns of sexual activity, condom use, contraceptive use, sexually transmitted infections (STIs), pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) and pregnancy, among adolescents with PCOS compared to adolescents without the condition. Method(s): A retrospective chart review of patients enrolled in an urban academic adolescent health clinic within a tertiary health system was performed. Electronic medical records were identified using ICD-9 codes for female patients aged 12-22 years old diagnosed with PCOS meeting the NIH criteria for diagnosis between July 2009 and December 2013 and compared to healthy female controls. Result(s): Charts of 229 patients with PCOS were identified and reviewed and compared to 223 healthy controls. Pearson chi-square test, Fisher's exact test and t-tests were used to compare PCOS patients to controls for descriptive purposes. Compared to healthy controls, females with PCOS group were more likely to have public insurance (p=0.0001), have educational attainment of less than or equal to a high school graduate (p<0.0001), have higher percentages of PID (p=0.0126) and have higher mean body mass indices (BMI) (p<0.0001). There was no statistically significant difference between age of menarche, age of coitarche, sexual activity status, prior pregnancies, or STIs between PCOS patients vs. controls. Logistic regression modeling was utilized for STIs and PID controlling for race, BMI, insurance, education, sexual activity status, lifetime partners and condom usage. There was no difference in STIs between adolescent females with PCOS vs. healthy controls. Adolescent females who were sexually active were more likely to have STIs (OR=8.8, 95%CI=(2.2, 35.6)) and those did not provide information about their number of sexual partners were more likely to have STIs (OR=17.3, 95% CI =(1.9, 158.9)) than those who reported this information. Adolescent females who reported always using condoms or provided no information on condom usage were less likely to have STIs (OR=0.29, 95% CI =(0.12, 0.67); OR=0.39, 95% CI =(0.16, 0.96) respectively) than those who "never" or "sometimes" reported using condoms. Adolescent females with PCOS were more likely to have PID (OR=4.7, 95% CI =(1.5, 14.3)) compared to healthy controls without PCOS. Conclusion(s): Adolescent patients with PCOS are as sexually active as their peers with no differences in age of menarche, age of coitarche, sexual activity status, prior pregnancies, or STIs vs. healthy controls. They were identified as more likely to have PID compared to their healthy control peers increasing their risk for future infertility. These results highlight the need for consistent counseling on safe sexual practices and consistent screening for STIs in this population. Educational Objective: To describe reproductive health patterns of adolescent female patients with polycystic ovarian syndrome versus controls.
