893. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 615242978
T1  - Study design for a pragmatic clinical trial of fatigue medications in multiple sclerosis
T3  - 2017 Americas Committee for Treatment and Research in Multiple Sclerosis Forum, ACTRIMS 2017. Orlando, FL United States.
A1  - Nourbakhsh B.
A1  - Revirajan N.
A1  - Waubant E. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Background: Fatigue is the most common and probably the most disabling symptom of MS that negatively impacts the quality of life and employment. Despite lack of high quality evidence from clinical trials, amantadine, modafinil and amphetamine-like psychostimulants are commonly used for the treatment of MS-related fatigue. Objective(s): To determine within-subject effect of treatment with amantadine versus modafinil versus methylphenidate versus placebo on MS fatigue and quality of life. We will also assess the safety and tolerability of these medications. Method(s): This is a randomized, placebo-controlled, crossover, 4-sequence, 4-period, double-blind (participants and investigators), multicenter trial of 3 commonly used and recommended medications for treatment of MS-related fatigue (amantadine, modafinil, methylphenidate) versus placebo in fatigued subjects with McDonald MS. Other inclusion criteria include: time since first reported MS symptoms at least 6 months, EDSS score between 0.0 - 7.0, fatigue reportedly present and screening modified fatigue impact scale (MFIS) score more than 38. Participants will be randomized to one of four predefined sequences of medication administration, comprised of four 6-week periods of receiving study medication (or placebo) and three 2-week washout periods between medication periods. In each period, patients will receive one of the study medications titrated over six weeks. The primary and secondary outcomes of the study will be assessed in the last week of the medication-administration period, while patient will be on the highest predefined or maximally tolerated doses of the study medication. Result(s): 136 participants will be randomized over two years in two centers in the United States (UCSF, Johns Hopkins) starting in the Spring 2017. Complete enrollment is expected by early 2019. The primary outcome of the study is the average MFIS score over 3 days while patients receive the maximally tolerated dose of each study medication (or placebo). Quality of life of the participants and safety and tolerability of the medications will also be assessed. Conclusion(s): Results of the proposed study funded by PCORI will provide evidence-based and personalized treatment options for patients affected by MS-related fatigue.
