AN  - 614602586
T1  - Comorbidities of hidradenitis suppurativa, multidisciplinary approach and patient support: A 3-year single center clinical experience
T3  - 6th Conference of the European Hidradenitis Suppurativa Foundation e.V., EHSF 2017. Copenhagen Denmark.
A1  - Manuelyan K.
A1  - Lavcheva R.
A1  - Gancheva D.
A1  - Deliyska R.
A1  - Hristakieva E. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) is a recurrent inflammatory disease, which has a significant impact on the quality of life. The condition is clinically presented with inflamed, painful nodules, sinus-tracts and/ or scarring in the inverse regions of the body. HS has been associated with several disorders like skin diseases, inflammatory conditions, endocrine and genetic disorders. Methods & Results: The overall number of patients with HS seen in the Clinic of Dermatology and Venereology in Stara Zagora, Bulgaria, within the three-year period was 107 (male 65: female 42). According to the Hurley staging system the distribution was as follows: stage I - 36 patients (34%); stage II - 47 patients (44%); stage III - 24 patients (22%). Risk factors of obesity and active smoking were seen in 25% and 67%, respectively. The observed comorbidities were follicular occlusion tetrad (including acne conglobata/severe acne vulgaris, pilonidal cyst), diabetes, polycystic ovary syndrome, autoimmune thyroiditis, vitiligo, deafness, squamous cell carcinoma, ankylosing spondylitis, pyoderma gangrenosum, ulcerative colitis, arterial hypertension and anaemia of chronic disease. Comorbidities required input from a multidisciplinary team. Patient support programs were developed. We present some of the more severe cases from our clinic of HS associated with other conditions. We also present the results after evaluation of DLQI in different stages of HS and also before and after wide excision with secondary healing. Patients in early stages had scores in the range of 2-5, while patients in advanced stages had higher scores of 10-29. Post-surgery the DLQI was significantly lower in the range of 1-5. Conclusion(s): Severe HS cases are more commonly associated with other diseases. Approximately 50% of the HS patients in II and III Hurley stage suffer from one or more comorbidities, which further decrease the quality of life and have implications on the treatment choice and outcome. Thus, a multidisciplinary approach is essential to patient care. Developing patient support programs is an integral part of successful treatment. Patients in early stages of HS have lower DLQI scores, while HS in Hurley stage II and III has a moderate to extreme effect on the quality of life. After surgery the DLQI score decreases significantly, showing that wide excision is a very effective treatment strategy.
